# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-silent-agreement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] The plot concerns Reuben (played by Davo Hardy), who overcomes a speech impediment with the use of Auslan, with help from his profoundly deaf boyfriend (played by Joshua Sealy).
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Having built up Reuben's confidence enough to encourage his higher ambitions, Derek contacts an Australian screen legend, Gareth (played by Paul Mercurio) to help mentor Reuben in his burgeoning career.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] But shortly after seeing the potential in Reuben's autobiographical screenplay, Gareth takes over the project for his own gain and sanitizes the story to suit a wider audience, thereby cutting Reuben out of the equation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Forced to draw upon the courage and self-actualization that he has gathered through the experience, Reuben stands up to his bully and wins the support of those who had once opposed him, for the greater moral good.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Davo Hardy has stated in interviews that the film was a response to his film mentors telling him he could not be a director because of his real-life stutter.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Reuben Heywood is an aspiring writer, who grapples with anxiety, manifesting as a stutter, while attempting to build a career as both a writer and actor.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] When a performance at an amateur theatre showcase goes awry, Reuben is bullied by the troupe leader and a sign language interpreter.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Derek Shanahan, a profoundly deaf man from the audience (played by Joshua Sealy) comes to vindicate him and the two form a friendship which quickly turns into a sexual relationship.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] As Derek and Reuben discuss their mutual ambitions within the arts and political activism, Reuben discloses his troubled past and the origins of his speech impediment.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Derek encourages Reuben to steer his work away from theater and into independent film, offering to support him, where needed.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Shortly after, Derek seeks out Reuben's dream mentor, Gareth Donahue (played by Paul Mercurio) to help him bring his story, titled *The Burden of Being Me* to the screen.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Gareth, meanwhile, has reached a low point in his career.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] He is over 50, lamenting his lost youth and fading career.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Hungry for a chance to make a comeback, Gareth agrees to meet with Reuben and discuss their collaboration on *The Burden of Being Me*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Derek is also present at the meeting and is quick to point out Gareth's self-obsessed narcissism. but Reuben overlooks his observations, blindsided by the support that Gareth offers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Derek's mother, Faye Shanahan, and sister, Courtney, are deeply protective of Derek and treat Reuben's artistic ambitions with skepticism.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Faye, a painter, discourages Derek's involvement with Reuben's filmmaking, in favor of noble causes to support deaf education and advocating human rights in the footsteps of Helen Keller.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Reuben recognizes the hypocrisy and continues to pursue his film with Derek and Gareth.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Almost immediately after receiving the script of *The Burden of Being Me*, Gareth begins to amend the characters and plot to suit him as both an actor and a producer.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] His wife, Lillian Donahue, a highly respected entertainment attorney, is captivated by the screenplay and recognizes Reuben as a talented writer.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] But Gareth uses his industry expertise and gas-lighting tactics to seize creative control from Reuben, while also manipulating Lillian to help him, using her long-delayed desire to have children as leverage for emotional blackmail.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Obediently, Lillian writes up contracts that highly favor Gareth's interests and leave Reuben empty handed.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Immediately conflicted by guilt, Lillian stands idly by, as Gareth pressures Reuben to sign the contracts and grant him 100% of the rights.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] When Reuben realizes that he has been swindled, Faye offers to help finance Reuben's next project, effectively giving her blessing for he and Derek to collaborate in the future.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] This offer is quickly retracted when Reuben accidentally makes a spectacle of himself at Courtney's engagement party and embarrasses the family.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Derek sides with Faye, citing that Reuben has acted in appropriately.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Reuben is asked to leave the party, at once.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Shortly after, Reuben receives an emotional call from Courtney, saying that Derek has suddenly died from an accident.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] At the funeral, Faye confronts Reuben, imploring him to continue honoring Derek's memory, but also to honor himself.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Meanwhile, Lillian reads an article about Reuben's stage play, dedicated to Derek's memory.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Gareth's only response is to make sure the stage play has no affiliation with the film he now owns the rights to, or else they'd have to sue.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Incensed at Gareth's heartlessness, Lillian lashes out at him and vows to reverse the contracts that she had made for Gareth.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Concluding that her chance to have children has passed her by, Lillian abandons Gareth and seeks Reuben out at the theater, where he and Derek met.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] She encourages him to rewrite his story from scratch and amend key elements, so that Gareth cannot claim copyright infringement.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Similarly, Faye reinstates her support of Reuben, around the time of her first Christmas since her son's death.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] One by one, Gareth's collaborators abandon his project and he is left without any supporters at around the time that Reuben develops his new film, *The Purpose of Being Me*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] At the a screening of his film, Reuben thanks the audience for attending, including those who may have originally discouraged him.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] He thanks them for providing the strength he needed to continue in his pursuits, even if it was only to prove them wrong.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] The film also brought Paul Mercurio back into the spotlight.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] On 11 April 2017, during a live interview for *The Morning Show*, the hosts Larry Emdur and Kylie Gillies attempted to discuss the 25-year anniversary of *Strictly Ballroom*, but Paul continued to steer the conversation back to *A Silent Agreement*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] He was cast in *Promised* a few months later.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] The film was submitted into many festivals for its use of Auslan, qualifying it as a foreign language film.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Many LGBT-related festivals and organisations to do with the deaf and disabilities were lauding of *A Silent Agreement* for its authentic depictions of deaf characters, using deaf actors.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] The DVD was released in Australia on 8 December 2018, after its extended festival screenings; including special seminar screenings for its educational importance in support of Auslan and speech pathology.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] LGBT streaming service Dekkoo began to distribute the film from June 2019.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] Amazon released an NTSC DVD in September 2019.
[src:a-silent-agreement/a-silent-agreement] From 2022, *A Silent Agreement*, along with the rest of Davo Hardy's films, were made available on his dedicated streaming website; www.davohardyfilms.com.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] It is best known as the world's biggest online shopping retailer and marketplace, offering a wide range of products and services.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon sells books, electronics, pharmaceuticals, car parts, video games, dining products, jewelry, food, music, and sports equipment.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The company has multiple subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services (AWS), which provides cloud computing; Zoox, a self-driving car division; Kuiper Systems, a satellite Internet provider; and Amazon Lab126, a computer hardware R&D provider.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Other subsidiaries include Ring, Twitch, IMDb, and Whole Foods Market.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Its acquisition of Whole Foods in August 2017 for US$13.4 billion substantially increased its market share and its presence as a physical retailer.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also distributes a variety of downloadable and streaming content through its Amazon Prime Video, MGM+, Amazon Music, Twitch, Audible, and Wondery units.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also produces consumer electronics, most notably Kindle e-readers, Echo devices, Fire tablets, and Fire TVs.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has a reputation as a disruptor of industries through technological innovation and aggressive reinvestment of profits into capital expenditures.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As of 2023, it is the world's largest online retailer and marketplace, smart speaker provider, cloud computing service provider through AWS, live-streaming service provider through Twitch, and Internet company as measured by revenue and market share.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2021, it surpassed Walmart as the world's largest retailer outside of China, driven in large part by its paid subscription plan, Amazon Prime, which has 200 million subscribers worldwide.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] It is the second-largest private employer in the United States and the second-largest company in the world and the United States by revenue as of 2024 (after Walmart).
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As of October 2024, Amazon is the 12th-most visited website in the world, and 84% of its traffic comes from the United States.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has been criticized for its business practices, including surveillance partnerships, poor working conditions, anti-union efforts, environmental harm, anticompetitive behavior, censorship controversies, and exploitative treatment of small businesses and suppliers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On July 5, 1994, Amazon was founded as "Cadabra" by Jeff Bezos, after he relocated from New York City to Bellevue, Washington, near Seattle, to operate an online bookstore.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Bezos chose the Seattle area for its abundance of technical talent from Microsoft and the University of Washington, as well as its smaller population for sales tax purposes and the proximity to a major book distribution warehouse in Roseburg, Oregon.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Other options Bezos considered included Portland, Oregon, and Boulder, Colorado.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] A few months later, in November 1994, Cadabra, which had been founded in the converted garage of Bezos's house for symbolic reasons, was renamed to Amazon.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On July 16, 1995, the Amazon website launched for public sales, initially sourcing its books directly from wholesalers and publishers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Bezos retained the URL www.relentless.com, which he purchased when considering a name for the company; it redirects to the Amazon homepage.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 1998, Amazon began selling music and videos, and began international operations by acquiring online sellers of books in the United Kingdom and Germany.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In the subsequent year, it initiated the sale of a diverse range of products, including music, video games, consumer electronics, home improvement items, software, games, and toys.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2002, the company launched Amazon Web Services (AWS), which initially focused on providing APIs for web developers to build web applications on top of Amazon's e-commerce platform.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2004, AWS was expanded to provide website popularity statistics and web crawler data from the Alexa Web Information Service.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] AWS later shifted toward providing enterprise services with Simple Storage Service (S3) in 2006, and Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) in 2008, allowing companies to rent data storage and computing power from Amazon.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2006, Amazon launched the*Fulfillment by Amazon*program, which allowed individuals and small companies (called "third-party sellers") to sell products through Amazon's warehouses and fulfillment infrastructure.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon purchased the Whole Foods Market supermarket chain in 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] It is the leading e-retailer in the United States with approximately US$178 billion net sales in 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] It has over 300 million active customer accounts globally.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon saw large growth during the COVID-19 pandemic, hiring more than 100,000 staff in the United States and Canada.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Some Amazon workers in the US, France, and Italy protested the company's decision to "run normal shifts" due to COVID-19's ease of spread in warehouses.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In Spain, the company faced legal complaints over its policies, while a group of US Senators wrote an open letter to Bezos expressing concerns about workplace safety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On February 2, 2021, Bezos announced that he would step down as CEO to become executive chair of Amazon's board.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The transition officially took place on July 5, 2021, with former CEO of AWS Andy Jassy replacing him as CEO.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In January 2023, Amazon cut over 18,000 jobs, primarily in consumer retail and its human resources division in an attempt to cut costs.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On November 8, 2023, a plan was adopted for Jeff Bezos to sell approximately 50 million shares of the company over the next year with a deadline of January 31, 2025.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The first step was the sale of 12 million shares for about $2 billion.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On February 26, 2024, Amazon became a component of the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On December 19, 2024, Amazon workers, led by the International Brotherhood of Teamsters labor union, went on strike against Amazon in at least four US states, with workers in other facilities in the United States being welcomed to join the strike as well.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On October 28, 2025, the company announced plans to reduce its corporate workforce by 14,000 positions, which has been reported as the largest round of job cuts by Amazon since 2022.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As part of this plan, Amazon is expected to fire about 370 people from its European headquarters in Luxembourg in December 2025 to early 2026.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced a second round of large-scale layoffs, affecting approximately 16,000 corporate employees.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] This followed the earlier reduction of 14,000 positions in October 2025.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] According to company statements and news reports, the layoffs were part of a broader effort to streamline operations, reduce bureaucracy, and adapt to changing business conditions, including the adoption of artificial intelligence technologies.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Affected employees were offered severance packages and support for internal job placement.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In January 2025, Amazon filed an objection to Saks Global’s bankruptcy financing plan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon invested $475 million into Saks’ acquisition of Neiman Marcus, and is now worried that Saks declaring bankruptcy would harm creditors and push the tech company further down the repayment pecking order.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon entered talks with OpenAI to invest up to $50 billion.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon historically has a deep strategic partnership with Anthropic, OpenAI's competitor.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon also laid off 16,000 employees in what is Amazon's second round of large-scale job reductions in three months due to AI.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In February 2026, Amazon said it expected to invest $12 billion in Louisiana as part of a plan to build data centers there.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] This plan will create 540 full-time jobs.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In March 2026, Amazon signed an energy pledge at the White House which required it to bear the cost of new electricity generation to power its data centers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon launched Amazon Supply Chain Services in May 2026.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon websites are country-specific (for example, amazon.com for the US and amazon.co.uk for UK) though some offer international shipping.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Visits to *amazon.com* grew from 615 million annual visitors in 2008, to more than 2 billion per month in 2022.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The e-commerce platform is the 12th most visited website in the world.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In February 2024, Amazon announced its first chatbot, "Rufus", for use in the US; in July it was widely available to all customers in the US.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] "Rufus" is now available in the US, India and the UK which helps the shoppers get product recommendations, get shopping list advice, compare products and see what other customers have responded to regarding their specific questions.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Results generated by Amazon's search engine are partly determined by promotional fees.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2004, Toys "R" Us sued Amazon, claiming that because of a perceived lack of variety in Toys "R" Us stock, Amazon had knowingly allowed third-party sellers to offer items on the service in categories that Toys "R" Us had been granted exclusivity.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2006, a court ruled in favor of Toys "R" Us, giving it the right to unwind its agreement with Amazon and establish its independent e-commerce website.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The company was later awarded $51 million in damages.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2001, Amazon entered into a similar agreement with Borders, under which Amazon would comanage Borders.com as a co-branded service.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Borders pulled out of the arrangement in 2007, with plans to also launch its own online store.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On October 18, 2011, Amazon.com announced a partnership with DC Comics for the exclusive digital rights to many popular comics, including *Superman*, *Batman*, *Green Lantern*, *Sandman*, and *Watchmen*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The partnership has caused well-known bookstores like Barnes & Noble to remove these titles from its shelves.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In November 2013, Amazon announced a partnership with the United States Postal Service to begin delivering orders on Sundays.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The service, included in Amazon's standard shipping rates, initiated in metropolitan areas of Greater Los Angeles and New York because of the high-volume and inability to deliver in a timely way, with plans to expand into Dallas, Houston, New Orleans and Phoenix by 2014.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In June 2017, Nike agreed to sell products through Amazon in exchange for better policing of counterfeit goods.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] This proved unsuccessful and Nike withdrew from the partnership in November 2019.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Companies including IKEA and Birkenstock also stopped selling through Amazon around the same time, citing similar frustrations over business practices and counterfeit goods.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In September 2017, Amazon ventured with one of its sellers JV Appario Retail owned by Patni Group which has recorded a total income of US$104.44 million (₹759 crore) in financial year 2017–2018.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As of October 11, 2017, Amazon Fresh sold a range of Booths branded products for home delivery in selected areas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In November 2018, Amazon reached an agreement with Apple Inc. to sell selected products through the service, via the company and selected Apple Authorized Resellers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As a result of this partnership, only Apple Authorized Resellers may sell Apple products on Amazon effective January 4, 2019.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On November 7, 2024, Amazon is reportedly discussing a second multi-billion dollar investment in AI startup Anthropic, following its initial $4 billion investment.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On 8 October 2025, Amazon launched prescription vending machines at One Medical clinics in Los Angeles.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The machines are operated by Amazon Pharmacy and are able to prescribe a range of common medications, such as antibiotics, inhalers and blood pressure treatments.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon sells many products under its own brand names, including phone chargers, batteries, and diaper wipes.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The AmazonBasics brand was introduced in 2009, and now features hundreds of product lines, including smartphone cases, computer mice, batteries, dumbbells, and dog crates.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon owned 34 private-label brands as of 2019.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] These brands account for 0.15% of Amazon's global sales, whereas the average for other large retailers is 18%.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Other Amazon retail brands include Presto!, Mama Bear, and Amazon Essentials.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon derives many of its sales (around 40% in 2008) from third-party sellers who sell products on Amazon.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Some other large e-commerce sellers use Amazon to sell their products in addition to selling them through their websites.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The sales are processed through Amazon.com and end up at individual sellers for processing and order fulfillment and Amazon leases space for these retailers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Small sellers of used and new goods go to Amazon Marketplace to offer goods at a fixed price.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Publishers can sign up as affiliates and receive a commission for referring customers to Amazon by placing links to Amazon on their websites if the referral results in a sale.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Worldwide, Amazon has "over 900,000 members" in its affiliate programs.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As of mid-2014, the Amazon Affiliate Program was used by 1.2% of all websites and was the second most popular advertising network after Google Ads.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] It is frequently used by websites and non-profits to provide a way for supporters to earn them a commission.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Associates can access the Amazon catalog directly on their websites by using the Amazon Web Services (AWS) XML service.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] A new affiliate product, aStore, allows Associates to embed a subset of Amazon products within another website, or linked to another website.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In June 2010, Amazon Seller Product Suggestions was launched to provide more transparency to sellers by recommending specific products to third-party sellers to sell on Amazon.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Products suggested are based on customers' browsing history.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] A link -- embedded in a book name in an online article in *The New Yorker* and prefixed *cna.st/affiliate-link/* (the magazine is owned by Condé Nast) -- automatically redirected when accessed to the appropriate *amazon.com* page for the book.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon allows users to submit reviews to the web page of each product.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Reviewers must rate the product on a rating scale from one to five stars.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon provides a badging option for reviewers that indicates the real name of the reviewer (based on confirmation of a credit card account) or that indicates that the reviewer is one of the top reviewers by popularity.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As of 16 December 2020, Amazon removed the ability of sellers and customers to comment on product reviews and purged their websites of all posted product review comments.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In an email to sellers, Amazon gave its rationale for removing this feature: "...the comments feature on customer reviews was rarely used." The remaining review response options are to indicate whether the reader finds the review helpful or to report that it violates Amazon policies (abuse).
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] If a review is given enough "helpful" hits, it appears on the front page of the product.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2010, Amazon was reported as being the largest single source of Internet consumer reviews.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] When publishers asked Bezos why Amazon would publish negative reviews, he defended the practice by claiming that Amazon.com was "taking a different approach...we want to make every book available—the good, the bad and the ugly...to let truth loose".
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] There have been cases of positive reviews being written and posted by public relations companies on behalf of their clients and instances of writers using pseudonyms to leave negative reviews of their rivals' works.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The Amazon sales rank (ASR) indicates the popularity of a product sold on any Amazon locale.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] It is a relative indicator of popularity that is updated hourly.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Effectively, it is a "best sellers list" for the millions of products stocked by Amazon.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] While the ASR has no direct effect on the sales of a product, it is used by Amazon to determine which products to include in its bestsellers lists.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Products that appear in these lists enjoy additional exposure on the Amazon website and this may lead to an increase in sales.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In particular, products that experience large jumps (up or down) in their sales ranks may be included within Amazon's lists of "movers and shakers"; such a listing provides additional exposure that might lead to an increase in sales.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] For competitive reasons, Amazon does not release actual sales figures to the public.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] However, Amazon has now begun to release point of sale data via the BookScan service to verified authors.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] While the ASR has been the source of much speculation by publishers, manufacturers, and marketers, Amazon itself does not release the details of its sales rank calculation algorithm.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In November 2015, Amazon opened a physical Amazon Books store in University Village in Seattle.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The store was 5,500 square feet and prices for all products matched those on its website.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon opened its tenth physical bookstore in 2017; media speculation at the time suggested that Amazon planned to eventually roll out 300 to 400 bookstores around the country.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] All of its locations were closed in 2022 along with other retail locations under the "Amazon 4-Star" brand.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In July 2016, the company announced that it was opening a 1,100,000 ft (335,280.0 m) square foot facility in Palmer Township in the Lehigh Valley region of eastern Pennsylvania.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As of 2024, Amazon is the Lehigh Valley region's third-largest employer.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In August 2019, Amazon applied to have a liquor store in San Francisco, as a means to ship beer and alcohol within the city.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2020, Amazon Fresh opened several physical stores in the US and the United Kingdom.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced it would close all of its Amazon Go and Amazon Fresh stores to shift focus to its online same-day delivery service and expand its Whole Foods Market business.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The closure affects 57 Fresh stores and 15 Amazon Go locations, some of which will be converted into Whole Foods stores.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has a number of products and services available, including its digital assistant Alexa, Amazon Music, and Prime Video for music and videos respectively, the Amazon Appstore for Android apps, the Kindle line of electronic paper e-readers, Fire and Fire HD color LCD tablets.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Audible provides audiobooks for purchase and listening.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In September 2021, Amazon announced the launch of Astro, its first household robot, powered by its Alexa smart home technology.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] This can be remote-controlled when not at home, to check on pets, people, or home security.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] It will send owners a notification if it detects something unusual.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In January 2023, Amazon announced the launch of RXPass, a prescription drug delivery service.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Prime members to pay a $5 monthly fee for access to 60 medications.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The service was launched immediately after the announcement except in states with specific prescription delivery requirements.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Beneficiaries of government healthcare programs such as Medicare and Medicaid will not be able to sign up for RXPass.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon owns over 100 subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services, Audible, Diapers.com, Goodreads, IMDb, Kiva Systems (now Amazon Robotics), One Medical, Shopbop, Teachstreet, Twitch, Zappos, and Zoox.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Bezos separately owns *The Washington Post* (through Nash Holdings, LLC), Blue Origin, Bezos Expeditions, Altos Labs, and other companies.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Live is a video e-commerce live-streaming service created to compete with live-streaming services.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The service allows users to stream live videos promoting or sponsoring products.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Users (mainly celebrities or Internet influencers) have the option to livestream on Amazon and add tags to additionally add context to the products they're selling or promoting.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Other users can join in and type in messages to send to a global chat on the livestream.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2019 Amazon launched an integrated platform into the Amazon website and application.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In 2023 roughly a billion total viewers watch Amazon Live across the United States and India.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The platform has also been integrated into Amazon Freevee and Amazon Prime Video.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Web Services (AWS) is a subsidiary of Amazon that provides on-demand cloud computing platforms and APIs to individuals, companies, and governments, on a metered pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] These cloud computing web services provide distributed computing processing capacity and software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As of 2021 Q4, AWS has 33% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 21%, and 10% respectively, according to Synergy Group.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Audible is a seller and producer of spoken audio entertainment, information, and educational programming on the Internet.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Audible sells digital audiobooks, radio and television programs, and audio versions of magazines and newspapers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Through its production arm, Audible Studios, Audible has also become the world's largest producer of downloadable audiobooks.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On January 31, 2008, Amazon announced it would buy Audible for about $300 million.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The deal closed in March 2008 and Audible became a subsidiary of Amazon.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Goodreads is a "social cataloging" website founded in December 2006 and launched in January 2007 by Otis Chandler, a software engineer, and entrepreneur, and Elizabeth Khuri.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The website allows individuals to freely search Goodreads' extensive user-populated database of books, annotations, and reviews.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Users can sign up and register books to generate library catalogs and reading lists.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] They can also create their groups of book suggestions and discussions.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In December 2007, the site had over 650,000 members, and over a million books had been added.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon bought the company in March 2013.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Ring is a home automation company founded by Jamie Siminoff in 2013.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] It is primarily known for its Wi-Fi powered smart doorbells, but manufactures other devices such as security cameras.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon bought Ring for US$1 billion in 2018.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Twitch is a live streaming platform for video, primarily oriented towards video gaming content.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Twitch was acquired by Amazon in August 2014 for $970 million.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The site's rapid growth had been boosted primarily by the prominence of major esports competitions on the service, leading *GameSpot* senior esports editor Rod Breslau to have described the service as "the ESPN of esports".
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As of 2015, the service had over 1.5 million broadcasters and 100 million monthly viewers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Whole Foods Market is an American supermarket chain exclusively featuring foods without artificial preservatives, colors, flavors, sweeteners, and hydrogenated fats.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon acquired Whole Foods for $13.7 billion in August 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Since acquiring Whole Foods, the company has launched its own chain of Fresh supermarkets and taken steps to integrate its online and physical grocery operations.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also has investments in renewable energy, including plans to fund four small nuclear reactors at the Xe-100 reactor site in Eastern Washington, and plans to expand its position into the Canadian market through an investment in a new plant in Alberta.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's global headquarters are in more than 40 owned and leased buildings spread across Seattle's adjacent South Lake Union, Denny Triangle, and Downtown neighborhoods.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The first 14 buildings Amazon occupied in South Lake Union were developed primarily by Vulcan, Inc. from 2008 onward, the first 11 of which were acquired from Vulcan in 2012 at a cost of $1.16 billion.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The company was previously headquartered in rented space within the Pacific Medical Center, located in the city's Beacon Hill neighborhood, from 1998 to 2011.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon is currently building a new four tower, four low-rise, complex in Seattle's Denny Triangle neighborhood to serve as the primary headquarters, though it will retain many of the earlier purchased buildings to house its more than 45,000 corporate employees in the Seattle area.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The plan for the new campus, designed by NBBJ and named "Rufus 2.0" after a dog who was a fixture of the company in its early days, was approved by the city of Seattle in 2012 and construction began the year after.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The first of the towers, nicknamed Doppler, opened on December 14, 2015.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's European headquarters are in Luxembourg's capital, Luxembourg.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Its UK headquarters are at Principal Place, Shoreditch, London.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On November 13, 2018, Amazon announced that it would divide the planned HQ2 between New York City and Northern Virginia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On February 14, 2019, Amazon canceled its plan for the HQ2 location in New York City.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon is also in the process of building a retail hub of operations center in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On August 21, 2019, Amazon opened its largest campus in the world at Nanakramguda in Hyderabad, India.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] It is the first Amazon-owned campus located outside the United States and features the single largest Amazon-owned building in the world.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The 9.5-acre campus houses over 15,000 employees.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon plans to build a major campus in Bellevue, Washington, a suburb of Seattle, that will host 15,000 employees by 2025.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The company opened its first Bellevue office in 2017, marking a return to the city since the company was founded there in 1995.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's largest building in the city is Sonic, a 42-story building developed by Vulcan Real Estate with 1 million square feet (93,000 m2) of office space.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The Bellevue campus will include the 43-story Bellevue 600 tower, which is planned to be the tallest building in the city and the tallest to be developed by Amazon.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] While much of Amazon's software development occurs in Seattle, the company employs software developers in centers across the globe.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Some of these sites are run by an Amazon subsidiary called A2Z Development.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has operated various retail store brands.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Most of the stores are located inside of the United States, but Whole Foods also operates stores in Canada and the United Kingdom, while Amazon Go has six locations in London under the Amazon Fresh name.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon uses many different transportation services to deliver packages.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon directly employs people to work at its warehouses, bulk distribution centers, staffed "Amazon Hub Locker+" locations, and delivery stations where drivers pick up packages.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] As of December 2020, it is not hiring delivery drivers as employees.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Rakuten Intelligence estimated that in 2020 in the United States, the proportion of last-mile deliveries was 56% by Amazon's directly contracted services (mostly in urban areas), 30% by the United States Postal Service (mostly in rural areas), and 14% by UPS.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In April 2021, Amazon reported to investors it had increased its in-house delivery capacity by 50% in the last 12 months (which included the first year of the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States).
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In addition to Amazon Lockers, Amazon has around 30 staffed pickup points in the United States and over 800 independent ones in India.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The US locations have large sets of Amazon Lockers and an area for customers to make returns.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The India locations are in existing retailers and have customers wait for a store employee to retrieve their package.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon first launched its distribution network in 1997 with two fulfillment centers in Seattle and New Castle, Delaware.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has several types of distribution facilities consisting of cross-dock centers, fulfillment centers, sortation centers, delivery stations, Prime now hubs, and Prime air hubs.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] There are 75 fulfillment centers and 25 sortation centers with over 125,000 employees.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Employees are responsible for five basic tasks: unpacking and inspecting incoming goods; placing goods in storage and recording their location; picking goods from their computer recorded locations to make up an individual shipment; sorting and packing orders; and shipping.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] A computer that records the location of goods and maps out routes for pickers plays a key role: employees carry hand-held computers which communicate with the central computer and monitor their rate of progress.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Some warehouses are partially automated with systems built by Amazon Robotics.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In September 2006, Amazon launched a program called FBA (Fulfillment By Amazon) whereby it could handle storage, packing and distribution of products and services for small sellers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers are large facilities with hundreds of employees, sometimes thousands.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] A picker may walk 10 or more miles a day.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In newer fulfillment centers, items are stored on pods and brought to pickers by robots (Amazon Robotics).
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In the United Kingdom, initial staffing was provided by Randstad NV and other temporary employment agencies.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In the United States, many workers are hired as Amazon employees and granted shares of stock or sign-on bonuses, while others are offered temporary seasonal positions.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] "When we have permanent positions available, we look to the top-performing temporary associates to fill them," said an Amazon spokesperson.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon acquired Kiva Systems, a warehouse automation company, in 2012.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers can also provide warehousing and order-fulfillment for third-party sellers, for an extra fee.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] Third-party sellers can use Fulfillment by Amazon (FBA) to ship for other platforms as well, such as eBay or their own websites.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] On March 20, 2020, Amazon agreed to remove metal detectors from its warehouses after a warehouse worker tested positive for COVID-19.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] In addition to removing metal detectors, Amazon enacted a "6 feet rule", which enforced a six-feet distance between warehouse employees.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p01] The Federal Public Health Emergency (PHE) for COVID-19 (which included social distancing) declared under Section 319 of the Public Health Service (PHS) Act, expired at the end of the day on May 11, 2023.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com is primarily a retail site with a sales revenue model; Amazon takes a small percentage of the sale price of each item that is sold through its website while also allowing companies to advertise their products by paying to be listed as featured products.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] As of 2018, Amazon.com is ranked eighth on the Fortune 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In Forbes Global 2000 2023 Amazon ranked 36th.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] For the fiscal year 2021, Amazon reported earnings of US$33.36 billion, with an annual revenue of US$469.82 billion, an increase of 21.7% over the previous fiscal cycle.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Since 2007 sales increased from 14.835 billion to 469.822 billion, due to continued business expansion.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Amazon's market capitalization went over US$1 trillion again in early February 2020 after the announcement of the fourth quarter 2019 results.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] During his tenure, Jeff Bezos had become renowned for his annual shareholder letters, which have gained similar notability to those of Warren Buffett.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] These annual letters gave an "invaluable window" into the famously "secretive" company, and revealed Bezos's perspectives and strategic focus.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] A common theme of these letters is Bezos's desire to instill customer-centricity (in his words, "customer obsession") at all levels of Amazon, notably by making all senior executives field customer support queries for a short time at Amazon call centers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] He also read many emails addressed by customers to his public email address.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] One of Bezos's most well-known internal memos was his mandate for "all teams" to "expose their data and functionality" through service interfaces "designed from the ground up to be externalizable".
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] This process, commonly known as a service-oriented architecture (SOA), resulted in mandatory dogfooding of services that would later be commercialized as part of AWS.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Amazon has used internal recognition programs such as the Just Do It Award to encourage employee initiative and experimentation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Amazon lobbies the United States federal government and state governments on multiple issues such as the enforcement of sales taxes on online sales, transportation safety, privacy and data protection and intellectual property.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] According to regulatory filings, Amazon.com focuses its lobbying on the United States Congress, the Federal Communications Commission and the Federal Reserve.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com spent roughly $3.5 million, $5 million and $9.5 million on lobbying, in 2013, 2014 and 2015, respectively.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In 2019, it spent $16.8 million and had a team of 104 lobbyists.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com was a corporate member of the American Legislative Exchange Council (ALEC) until it dropped membership following protests at its shareholders' meeting on May 24, 2012.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In 2014, Amazon expanded its lobbying practices as it prepared to lobby the Federal Aviation Administration to approve its drone delivery program, hiring the Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld lobbying firm in June.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Amazon and its lobbyists have visited with Federal Aviation Administration officials and aviation committees in Washington, D.C. to explain its plans to deliver packages.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In September 2020 this moved one step closer with the granting of a critical certificate by the FAA.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] During the second Trump Administration, Amazon donated several times to various events and aspects of his presidency.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Along with several other major companies, Amazon donated $1 million to Trump's inaugural fund.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In April 2025, Amazon was a corporate sponsor of the White House Easter Egg Roll, after Donald Trump solicited corporate sponsors for the event for the first time.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In October 2025, Amazon was listed among the donors funding the construction of the White House State Ballroom.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Amazon lobbies on climate policy internationally.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In the US, following Trump’s 2025 inauguration, Amazon began frequent engagements with the executive branch to advocate for permitting reform and energy development to support data center growth.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In July 2025, Amazon joined policymakers at the Pennsylvania Energy and Innovation Summit, where it supported the development of nuclear energy to meet growing electricity demand, and lobbied for permitting reform to support grid development nationwide.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] A December 2025 DeSmog article reported that the company’s sponsorship came alongside several organizations that had supported climate change denial, and a continued role for fossil fuels to meet growing energy demand.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Criticism has also concerned various decisions over whether to censor or publish content such as the WikiLeaks website, works containing libel, anti-LGBT merchandise, and material facilitating dog fighting, cockfighting, or pedophile activities.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] An article published by *Time* in the wake of social media website Parler's termination of service by Amazon Web Service highlights the power companies like Amazon now have over the internet.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In December 2011, Amazon faced a backlash from small businesses for running a one-day deal to promote its new Price Check app.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Shoppers who used the app to check prices in a brick-and-mortar store were offered a 5% discount to purchase the same item from Amazon.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Companies like Groupon, eBay and Taap have countered Amazon's promotion by offering $10 off from its products.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] The company has also faced accusations of putting undue pressure on suppliers to maintain and extend its profitability.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In 2019, Amazon banned selling skin-lightening products after pushback from Minnesota health and environmental activists.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In 2022, a lawsuit filed by state attorney-general Letitia James was dismissed by the New York state court of appeals.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] After the COVID-19 pandemic, Amazon faced criticism for complying, under pressure from the Biden Administration, to "reduce the visibility" of books critical of the COVID-19 vaccine, which was revealed after Rep.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Jim Jordan (acting on behalf of the House Judiciary Committee) subpoenaed emails between the company and the Biden Administration.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Amazon Prime has been criticized for its vehicles systemically double parking, blocking bike lanes, and otherwise violating traffic laws while dropping off packages, contributing to traffic congestion and endangering other road users.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Jane Friedman discovered six listings of books fraudulently using her name, on Amazon and Goodreads.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In 2024, following years of criticism for providing law enforcement footage in the custody of Ring (a home security company owned by Amazon) without a warrant, Ring has halted this practice.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] It received cautious praise from privacy-focused organizations such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation for this change.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In February 2025, Sky accused Amazon of not doing enough to prevent the piracy of its sports rights via "jailbroken" Fire Sticks.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Project Nimbus is a contract by which Amazon and Google provide Israel and its military with artificial intelligence, machine learning, and other cloud-computing services.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] The contract has been criticized by shareholders and employees concerned that the project may lead to abuses of Palestinian human rights in the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In October 2025, Amazon suspended an employee who posted messages to the company's Slack and wrote a letter to Andy Jassy criticizing Nimbus.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] On July 22, 2025, Amazon announced its plan to acquire San Francisco-based startup Bee AI.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] Bee produces a wristband, similar to most modern smartwatches, equipped with AI and microphones.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] The wristband is capable of providing summaries of conversations and reminders of tasks, effectively serving as a 24/7 note taker.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] News outlets criticize the fact that the devices saves transcripts, potentially utilizing it to train generative AI models which require vast quantities of data.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] In January 2026, Amazon sent a notice out to cloud staffers in an apparent error acknowledging “organizational changes” at the company.
[src:a-silent-agreement/amazon-company-p02] The note also mentioned a "Project Dawn" which was cancelled, although it is unclear what the project is about.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety is a feeling of uneasiness and worry, usually generalized and unfocused as an overreaction to a situation that is only subjectively seen as menacing.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] It is often accompanied by muscular tension, restlessness, fatigue, inability to catch one's breath, tightness in the abdominal region, nausea, and problems in concentration.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety is closely related to fear, which is a response to a real or perceived immediate threat (fight-or-flight response); anxiety involves the expectation of a future threat, including dread.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] People facing anxiety may withdraw from situations which have provoked anxiety in the past.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The emotion appropriate time periods in response to specific events, and thus turn into one of the multiple anxiety disorders (e.g., generalized anxiety disorder, panic disorder).
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The difference between *anxiety disorder* and *anxiety* (as a normal emotion) is that people with an anxiety disorder experience anxiety excessively or persistently for approximately 6 months, or even during shorter time periods in children.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety disorders are among the most persistent mental problems and often last decades.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety can also be experienced within other mental disorders (e.g., obsessive–compulsive disorder, post-traumatic stress disorder).
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety is distinguished from fear, which is an appropriate cognitive and emotional response to a perceived threat.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Fear is related to the specific behaviors of fight-or-flight responses, defensive behavior or escape.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] There is a false presumption that often circulates that anxiety only occurs in situations perceived as uncontrollable or unavoidable, but this is not always so.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] David Barlow defines anxiety as "a future-oriented mood state in which one is not ready or prepared to attempt to cope with upcoming negative events," and that it is a distinction between future and present dangers which divides anxiety and fear.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Another description of anxiety is agony, dread, terror, or even apprehension.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] In positive psychology, anxiety is described as the mental state that results from a difficult challenge for which the subject has insufficient coping skills.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Fear and anxiety can be differentiated into four domains: (1) duration of emotional experience, (2) temporal focus, (3) specificity of the threat, and (4) motivated direction.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Fear is short-lived, present-focused, geared towards a specific threat, and facilitates escape from threat.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] On the other hand, anxiety is long-acting, future-focused, broadly focused towards a diffuse threat, and promotes excessive caution while approaching a potential threat and interferes with constructive coping.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] LeDoux and Lisa Feldman Barrett have both sought to separate automatic threat responses from additional associated cognitive activity within anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Evolutionary psychiatry and evolutionary psychology interpret anxiety as an evolved defenses that helps organisms avoid potential threats; by design, such defenses can produce "false alarms" when the cost of a missed danger would be high (sometimes described as a "smoke‑detector" principle).
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Contemporary reviews stress that this framing does not treat anxiety disorders as adaptive, but rather as dysregulations or context‑insensitive activation of otherwise useful systems; the perspective is used for explanation and psychoeducation, not as a specific therapy.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety can be experienced with long, drawn-out daily symptoms that reduce quality of life, known as chronic (or generalized) anxiety, or it can be experienced in short spurts with sporadic, stressful panic attacks, known as acute anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Symptoms of anxiety can range in number, intensity, and frequency, depending on the person.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] However, most people do not suffer from chronic anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety can induce several psychological pains (e.g., depression) or mental disorders, and may lead to self-harm or suicide.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The behavioral effects of anxiety may include withdrawal from situations which have provoked anxiety or negative feelings in the past.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Other effects may include changes in sleeping patterns, changes in habits, an increase or decrease in food intake, and increased motor tension (such as foot tapping).
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The emotional effects of anxiety may include feelings of apprehension or dread, trouble concentrating, feeling tense or jumpy, anticipating the worst, irritability, restlessness, watching for signs of danger, and a feeling of emptiness.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] It may also include a feeling of helplessness.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The cognitive effects of anxiety may include thoughts about suspected dangers, such as an irrational fear of dying or having a heart attack, when in reality, all one is experiencing is mild chest pain, for example.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Existential anxiety can occur when a person faces angst, an existential crisis, or nihilistic feelings.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] People can also face mathematical anxiety, somatic anxiety, stage fright, or test anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Social anxiety refers to a fear of rejection and negative evaluation (being judged) by other people.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The philosopher Søren Kierkegaard, in *The Concept of Anxiety* (1844), described anxiety or dread associated with the "dizziness of freedom" and suggested the possibility for positive resolution of anxiety through the self-conscious exercise of responsibility and choosing.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] In *Art and Artist* (1932), the psychologist Otto Rank wrote that the psychological trauma of birth was the pre-eminent human symbol of existential anxiety and encompasses the creative person's simultaneous fear of – and desire for – separation, individuation, and differentiation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] According to Tillich, the last of these three types of existential anxiety is predominant in modern times, while the others were predominant earlier.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Tillich argues that spiritual anxiety can either be accepted as part of the human condition or resisted with negative consequences.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] In its pathological form, it may "drive the person toward the creation of certitude in systems of meaning which are supported by tradition and authority" even though such "undoubted certitude is not built on the rock of reality".
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] According to Viktor Frankl, the author of *Man's Search for Meaning*, when a person is faced with extreme mortal dangers, the most basic of all human wishes is to find a meaning of life to combat the "trauma of nonbeing" as death is near.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Depending on the source of the threat, psychoanalytic theory distinguishes three types of anxiety: realistic, neurotic and moral.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] According to the Yerkes-Dodson law, an optimal level of arousal is necessary to best complete a task such as an exam, performance, or competitive event.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] However, when the anxiety or level of arousal exceeds that optimum, the result is a decline in performance.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Test anxiety is the uneasiness, apprehension, or nervousness felt by students who have a fear of failing an exam.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Students who have test anxiety may experience any of the following: the association of grades with personal worth; fear of embarrassment by a teacher; fear of alienation from parents or friends; time pressures; or feeling a loss of control.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Sweating, dizziness, headaches, racing heartbeats, nausea, fidgeting, uncontrollable crying or laughing and drumming on a desk are all common.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Because test anxiety hinges on fear of negative evaluation, debate exists as to whether test anxiety is itself a unique anxiety disorder or whether it is a specific type of social phobia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The DSM-IV classifies test anxiety as a type of social phobia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Research indicates that test anxiety among U.S. high-school and college students has been rising since the late 1950s.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Test anxiety remains a challenge for students, regardless of age, and has considerable physiological and psychological impacts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Management of test anxiety focuses on achieving relaxation and developing mechanisms to manage anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The routine practice of slow, Device-Guided Breathing (DGB) is a major component of behavioral treatments for anxiety conditions.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Performance anxiety and competitive anxiety (competitive trait anxiety, competitive state anxiety) happen when an individual's performance is measured against others.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] An important distinction between competitive and non-competitive anxiety is that competitive anxiety makes people view their performance as a threat.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] As a result, they experience a drop in their ordinary ability, whether physical or mental, due to that perceived stress.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Competitive anxiety is caused by a range of internal factors, including high expectations, outside pressure, lack of experience, and external factors like the location of a competition.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] It commonly occurs in those participating in high-pressure activities like sports and debates.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Some common symptoms of competitive anxiety include muscle tension, fatigue, weakness, a sense of panic, apprehensiveness, and panic attacks.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] There are 4 major theories of how anxiety affects performance: Drive theory, Inverted U theory, Reversal theory, and The Zone of Optimal Functioning theory.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The *Inverted U theory* is based on the idea that performance peaks at a moderate stress level.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] It is called Inverted U theory because the graph that plots performance against anxiety looks like an inverted "U".
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The *Zone of Optimal Functioning theory* proposes that there is a zone where positive and negative emotions are in a balance which lead to feelings of dissociation and intense concentration, optimizing the individual's performance levels.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Humans generally require social acceptance and thus sometimes dread the disapproval of others.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Apprehension of being judged by others may cause anxiety in social environments.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety during social interactions, particularly between strangers, is common among young people.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] It may persist into adulthood and become social anxiety or social phobia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] "Stranger anxiety" in small children is not considered a phobia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] In adults, an excessive fear of other people is not a developmentally common stage; it is called social anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] According to Cutting, social phobic do not fear the crowd but the fact that they may be judged negatively.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Social anxiety varies in degree and severity.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] For some people, it is characterized by experiencing discomfort or awkwardness during physical social contact (e.g. embracing, shaking hands, etc.), while in other cases it can lead to a fear of interacting with unfamiliar people altogether.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Those with this condition may restrict their lifestyles to accommodate the anxiety, minimizing social interaction whenever possible.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Social anxiety also forms a core aspect of certain personality disorders, including avoidant personality disorder.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] To the extent that a person is fearful of social encounters with unfamiliar others, some people may experience anxiety particularly during interactions with outgroup members, or people who share different group memberships (i.e., by race, ethnicity, class, gender, etc.).
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Depending on the nature of the antecedent relations, cognitions, and situational factors, intergroup contact may be stressful and lead to feelings of anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] This apprehension or fear of contact with outgroup members is often called interracial or intergroup anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] As is the case with the more generalized forms of social anxiety, intergroup anxiety has behavioral, cognitive, and affective effects.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] For instance, increases in schematic processing and simplified information processing can occur when anxiety is high.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Indeed, such is consistent with related work on attentional bias in implicit memory.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Additionally recent research has found that implicit racial evaluations (i.e. automatic prejudiced attitudes) can be amplified during intergroup interaction.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Negative experiences have been illustrated in producing not only negative expectations, but also avoidant, or antagonistic, behavior such as hostility.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Furthermore, when compared to anxiety levels and cognitive effort (e.g., impression management and self-presentation) in intragroup contexts, levels and depletion of resources may be exacerbated in the intergroup situation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety can be either a short-term "state" or a long-term "personality trait".
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Trait anxiety reflects a stable tendency across the lifespan of responding with acute, state anxiety in the anticipation of threatening situations (whether they are actually deemed threatening or not).
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] A meta-analysis showed that a high level of neuroticism is a risk factor for development of anxiety symptoms and disorders.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Such anxiety may be conscious or unconscious.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Personality can also be a trait leading to anxiety and depression and their persistence.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Through experience, many find it difficult to collect themselves due to their own personal nature.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety induced by the need to choose between similar options is recognized as a problem for some individuals and for organizations.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] In 2004, Capgemini wrote: "Today we're all faced with greater choice, more competition and less time to consider our options or seek out the right advice." Overthinking a choice is called analysis paralysis.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] In a decision context, unpredictability or uncertainty may trigger emotional responses in anxious individuals that systematically alter decision-making.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] There are primarily two forms of this anxiety type.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The first form refers to a choice in which there are multiple potential outcomes with known or calculable probabilities.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The second form refers to the uncertainty and ambiguity related to a decision context in which there are multiple possible outcomes with unknown probabilities.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Panic disorder may share symptoms of stress and anxiety, but it is actually very different.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Panic disorder is an anxiety disorder that occurs without any triggers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Department of Health and Human Services, this disorder can be distinguished by unexpected and repeated episodes of intense fear.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Someone with panic disorder will eventually develop constant fear of another attack and as this progresses it will begin to affect daily functioning and an individual's general quality of life.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] It is reported by the Cleveland Clinic that panic disorder affects 2 to 3 percent of adult Americans and can begin around the time of the teenage and early adult years.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Some symptoms include: difficulty breathing, chest pain, dizziness, trembling or shaking, feeling faint, nausea, fear that you are losing control or are about to die.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Even though they have these symptoms during an attack, the main symptom is the persistent fear of having future panic attacks.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety disorders are a group of mental disorders characterized by exaggerated feelings of anxiety and fear responses.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety is a worry about future events and fear is a reaction to current events.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] These feelings may cause physical symptoms, such as a fast heart rate and shakiness.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] There are a number of anxiety disorders: including generalized anxiety disorder, specific phobia, social anxiety disorder, separation anxiety disorder, agoraphobia, panic disorder, and selective mutism.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The disorder differs by what results in the symptoms.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] People often have more than one anxiety disorder.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety disorders are caused by a complex combination of genetic and environmental factors.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] To be diagnosed, symptoms typically need to be present for at least six months, be more than would be expected for the situation, and decrease a person's ability to function in their daily lives.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Other problems that may result in similar symptoms include hyperthyroidism, heart disease, caffeine, alcohol, or cannabis use, and withdrawal from certain drugs, among others.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Without treatment, anxiety disorders tend to remain.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Treatment may include lifestyle changes, counselling, and medications.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Counselling is typically with a type of cognitive behavioral therapy.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Medications, such as antidepressants or beta blockers, may improve symptoms.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] A 2023 review found that regular physical activity is effective for reducing anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] About 12% of people are affected by an anxiety disorder in a given year and between 12% and 30% are affected at some point in their life.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] They occur about twice as often in women than they do in men, and generally begin before the age of 25.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The most common anxiety disorders are specific phobias, which affect nearly 12% of people, and social anxiety disorder, which affects 10% of people at some point in their life.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] They affect those between the ages of 15 and 35 the most and become less common after the age of 55.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Rates appear to be higher in the United States and Europe.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety can be either a short-term "state" or a long-term "trait".
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Whereas trait anxiety represents worrying about future events, anxiety disorders are a group of mental disorders characterized by feelings of anxiety and fears.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] When you notice body sensations, you worry about what they might mean for your physical and/or psychological well-being.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The trigger stimulus does not have to be an external stimulus but can be an internal one, as some people are particularly sensitive to body signals.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Thoughts and memories may lead to you to worry about your physical and/or psychological well-being.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] We do not need to be in the presence of an external or internal stimulus to be anxious.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] An episodic memory of a past trauma or of a panic attack in the past is sufficient to activate the defense circuits.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Thoughts and memories may result in existential dread, such as worry about leading a meaningful life or the eventuality of death.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Examples are contemplations of whether one's life has been meaningful, the inevitability of death, or the difficulty of making decisions that have a moral value.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] These do not necessarily activate defensive systems; they are more or less pure forms of cognitive anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety disorders often occur with other mental health disorders, particularly major depressive disorder, bipolar disorder, eating disorders, or certain personality disorders.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] It also commonly occurs with personality traits such as neuroticism.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] This observed co-occurrence is partly due to genetic and environmental influences shared between these traits and anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] It is common for those with obsessive–compulsive disorder to experience anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety is also commonly found in those who experience panic disorders, phobic anxiety disorders, severe stress, dissociative disorders, somatoform disorders, and some neurotic disorders.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety has also been linked to the experience of intrusive thoughts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Studies have revealed that individuals who experience high levels of anxiety (also known as clinical anxiety) are highly vulnerable to the experience of intense intrusive thoughts or psychological disorders that are characterized by intrusive thoughts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety disorders are partly genetic, with twin studies suggesting 30–40% genetic influence on individual differences in anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Environmental factors are also important.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Twin studies show that individual-specific environments have a large influence on anxiety, whereas shared environmental influences (environments that affect twins in the same way) operate during childhood but decline through adolescence.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Specific measured 'environments' that have been associated with anxiety include child abuse, family history of mental health disorders, and poverty.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety is also associated with drug use, including alcohol and caffeine, as well as benzodiazepines, which are often prescribed to treat anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Genetics and family history (e.g. parental anxiety) may put an individual at increased risk of an anxiety disorder, but generally external stimuli will trigger its onset or exacerbation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Estimates of genetic influence on anxiety, based on studies of twins, range from 25 to 40% depending on the specific type and age-group under study.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] For example, genetic differences account for about 43% of variance in panic disorder and 28% in generalized anxiety disorder.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Longitudinal twin studies have shown the moderate stability of anxiety from childhood through to adulthood is mainly influenced by stability in genetic influence.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] When investigating how anxiety is passed on from parents to children, it is important to account for sharing of genes as well as environments, for example using the intergenerational children-of-twins design.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Many studies in the past used a candidate gene approach to test whether single genes were associated with anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] These investigations were based on hypotheses about how certain known genes influence neurotransmitters (such as serotonin and norepinephrine) and hormones (such as cortisol) that are implicated in anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] None of these findings are well replicated, with the possible exception of TMEM132D, COMT and MAO-A.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The reason that most candidate gene findings have not replicated is that anxiety is a complex trait that is influenced by many genomic variants, each of which has a small effect on its own.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Increasingly, studies of anxiety are using a hypothesis-free approach to look for parts of the genome that are implicated in anxiety using big enough samples to find associations with variants that have small effects.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The largest explorations of the common genetic architecture of anxiety have been facilitated by the UK Biobank, the ANGST consortium and the CRC Fear, Anxiety and Anxiety Disorders.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] These changes can lead to transgenerational stress inheritance.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Epigenetic modifications play a role in the development and heritability of these disorders and related symptoms.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] For example, regulation of the hypothalamus-pituitary-adrenal axis by glucocorticoids plays a major role in stress response and is known to be epigenetically regulated.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] As of 2015 most work has been done in animal models in laboratories, and little work has been done in humans; the work is not yet applicable to clinical psychiatry.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Stress-induced epigenetic changes, particularly to genes that effect the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal (HPA) axis, persist into future generations, negatively impacting the capacity of offspring to adapt to stress.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Early life experiences, even when generations removed, can cause permanent epigenetic modifications of DNA resulting in changes in gene expression, endocrine function and metabolism.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] These heritable epigenetic modifications include DNA methylation of the promoter regions of genes that affect sensitivity to stress.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Many medical conditions can cause anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] This includes conditions that affect the ability to breathe, like COPD and asthma, and the difficulty in breathing that often occurs near death.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Conditions that cause abdominal pain or chest pain can cause anxiety and may in some cases be a somatization of anxiety; the same is true for some sexual dysfunctions.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Conditions that affect the face or the skin can cause social anxiety especially among adolescents, and developmental disabilities often lead to social anxiety for children as well.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Life-threatening conditions like cancer also cause anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Furthermore, certain organic diseases may present with anxiety or symptoms that mimic anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Several drugs can cause or worsen anxiety, whether in intoxication, withdrawal or as side effect.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] These include alcohol, tobacco, sedatives (including prescription benzodiazepines), opioids (including prescription pain killers and illicit drugs like heroin), stimulants (such as caffeine, cocaine and amphetamines), hallucinogens, and inhalants.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] While many often report self-medicating anxiety with these substances, improvements in anxiety from drugs are usually short-lived (with worsening of anxiety in the long term, sometimes with acute anxiety as soon as the drug effects wear off) and tend to be exaggerated.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Acute exposure to toxic levels of benzene may cause euphoria, anxiety, and irritability lasting up to 2 weeks after the exposure.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Poor coping skills (e.g., rigidity/inflexible problem solving, denial, avoidance, impulsivity, extreme self-expectation, negative thoughts, affective instability, and inability to focus on problems) are associated with anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety is also linked and perpetuated by the person's own pessimistic outcome expectancy and how they cope with feedback negativity.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Temperament (e.g., neuroticism) and attitudes (e.g. pessimism) have been found to be risk factors for anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Cognitive distortions such as overgeneralizing, catastrophizing, mind reading, emotional reasoning, binocular trick, and mental filter can result in anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] For example, an overgeneralized belief that something bad "always" happens may lead someone to have excessive fears of even minimally risky situations and to avoid benign social situations due to anticipatory anxiety of embarrassment.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] In addition, those who have high anxiety can also create future stressful life events.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Together, these findings suggest that anxious thoughts can lead to anticipatory anxiety as well as stressful events, which in turn cause more anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Such unhealthy thoughts can be targets for successful treatment with cognitive therapy.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] For example, persistent parental discouragement of anger may result in repression/suppression of angry feelings which manifests as gastrointestinal distress (somatization) when provoked by another while the anger remains unconscious and outside the individual's awareness.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Such conflicts can be targets for successful treatment with psychodynamic therapy.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] While psychodynamic therapy tends to explore the underlying roots of anxiety, cognitive behavioral therapy has also been shown to be a successful treatment for anxiety by altering irrational thoughts and unwanted behaviors .
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] An evolutionary psychology explanation is that increased anxiety serves the purpose of increased vigilance regarding potential threats in the environment as well as increased tendency to take proactive actions regarding such possible threats.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] This may cause false positive reactions but an individual with anxiety may also avoid real threats.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] This may explain why anxious people are less likely to die due to accidents.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] There is ample empirical evidence that anxiety can have adaptive value.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Within a school, timid fish are more likely than bold fish to survive a predator.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] When people are confronted with unpleasant and potentially harmful stimuli such as foul odors or tastes, PET-scans show increased blood flow in the amygdala.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] In these studies, the participants also reported moderate anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] This might indicate that anxiety is a protective mechanism designed to prevent the organism from engaging in potentially harmful behaviors.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] A 2019 comprehensive systematic review of over 50 studies showed that food insecurity in the United States is strongly associated with depression, anxiety, and sleep disorders.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Food-insecure individuals had an almost 3 fold risk increase of testing positive for anxiety when compared to food-secure individuals.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Contextual factors that are thought to contribute to anxiety include gender socialization and learning experiences.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] In particular, learning mastery (the degree to which people perceive their lives to be under their own control) and instrumentality, which includes such traits as self-confidence, self-efficacy, independence, and competitiveness fully mediate the relation between gender and anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] That is, though gender differences in anxiety exist, with higher levels of anxiety in women compared to men, gender socialization and learning mastery explain these gender differences.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The first step in the management of a person with anxiety symptoms involves evaluating the possible presence of an underlying medical cause, the recognition of which is essential in order to decide the correct treatment.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety symptoms may mask an organic disease, or appear associated with or as a result of a medical disorder.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Anxiety is considered to be a serious psychiatric illness that has an unknown true pervasiveness due to affected individuals not asking for proper treatment or aid, and due to professionals missing the diagnosis.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) is effective for anxiety disorders and is a first line treatment.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] CBT appears to be equally effective when carried out via the internet.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] While evidence for mental health apps is promising, it is preliminary.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Psychopharmacological treatment can be used in parallel to CBT or can be used alone.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] As a general rule, most anxiety disorders respond well to first-line agents.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Such drugs, also used as antidepressants, are the selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) and serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors (SNRIs), that work by blocking the reuptake of specific neurotransmitters and resulting in the increase in availability of these neurotransmitters.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Additionally, benzodiazepines are often prescribed to individuals with anxiety disorder.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Benzodiazepines produce an anxiolytic response by modulating GABAA receptor and increasing its receptor binding.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] However, they should not usually be given for longer than 2–4 weeks.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The only medications National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence recommends for the longer-term management of anxiety are antidepressants, due to rapid development of tolerance, addiction and physical dependence during benzodiazepine therapy.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] A third common treatment involves a category of drug known as serotonin agonists, such as those that belong to azapirone class.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] This category of drug works by initiating a physiological response at 5-HT1A receptor by increasing the action of serotonin at this receptor.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Other treatment options include pregabalin, tricyclic or tetracyclic antidepressants (such as mirtazapine), and moclobemide, among others.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] The above risk factors give natural avenues for prevention.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Psychological or educational interventions have a small yet statistically significant benefit for the prevention of anxiety in varied population types.
[src:a-silent-agreement/anxiety] Improvement in dietary intake and habits may also help lower the risk of anxiety.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan was recognised by the Australian government as a "community language other than English" and the preferred language of the deaf community in policy statements in 1987 and 1991.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] However, this recognition has yet to filter through to many institutions, government departments, and professionals who work with deaf people.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The emerging status of Auslan has gone hand-in-hand with the advancement of the deaf community in Australia, beginning in the early 1980s.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] In 1982, the registration of the first sign language interpreters by NAATI, a newly established regulatory body for interpreting and translating, accorded a sense of legitimacy to Auslan, furthered by the publishing of the first dictionary of Auslan in 1989 (Johnston, 1989).
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Boosted by the 1992 enactment of the federal Disability Discrimination Act, Auslan/English interpreters are also increasingly provided in tertiary education.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Today there is a growing number of courses teaching Auslan as a second language, from an elective language subject offered by some secondary schools to a two-year full-time diploma at TAFE.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan content on television in Australia is limited.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] For some time, "Deaf TV", which was entirely in Auslan and was produced by deaf volunteers, aired on community television station Channel 31 in Melbourne.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Auslan experienced a period of increased visibility through press conferences from federal and state leaders and health officials, which invariably featured Auslan interpreters.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Since 2020, the ABC News channel's Sunday 5pm bulletin has included Auslan interpretation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan Day is celebrated on 13 April each year.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] This date was chosen as the anniversary of the publication of the first Auslan dictionary in 1989.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The Young Australian of the Year for 2015, Drisana Levitzke-Gray, is a strong proponent of Auslan and, in her acceptance speech using Auslan, called on the Government of Australia, and Australians, to learn and use Auslan as a natural language, as a human right for Australians.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan evolved from sign language varieties brought to Australia during the nineteenth century from Britain and Ireland.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The earliest record of a deaf Australian was convict Elizabeth Steel, who arrived in 1790 on the Second Fleet ship "Lady Juliana".
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] There is as yet no historical evidence, however, that she used a sign language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] One of the first known signing Deaf immigrants was the engraver John Carmichael who arrived in Sydney in 1825 from Edinburgh.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] He had been to a Deaf school there, and was known as a good storyteller in sign language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Thirty-five years later, in 1860, a school for the deaf was established by another deaf Scotsman, Thomas Pattison—the Royal Institute for Deaf and Blind Children in New South Wales.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] In Victoria just a few weeks later, the Victorian College for the Deaf was founded by a deaf Englishman, Frederick J Rose, who had been educated at the Old Kent Road School in London.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] These schools and others had an enormous role in the development of Auslan, as they were the first contact with sign language for many deaf children.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Because they were residential boarding schools, they provided ample opportunity for the language to thrive, even though in many schools, signing was banned from the classroom for much of the 20th century.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Irish Sign Language (ISL) also had an influence on the development of Auslan, as it was used in Roman Catholic deaf schools until the 1950s, especially in Sydney.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The first Catholic school for deaf children was established in 1875 by Irish nuns.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] As such, like Auslan evolving from BSL, Australian Irish Sign Language (or AISL) was born.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Unlike British Sign Language, both ISL and AISL use a one-handed alphabet originating in French Sign Language (LSF), and although this alphabet has now almost disappeared from Australia, some initialised signs from the ISL/AISL manual alphabet are still used in Auslan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The language contact post-secondary education between Australian ISL users and 'Australian BSL' users accounts for some of the dialectal differences seen between modern BSL and Auslan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] In more recent times, Auslan has seen a significant amount of lexical borrowing from American Sign Language (ASL), especially in signs for technical terms.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Some of these arose from the Signed English educational philosophies of the 1970s and 80s, when a committee looking for signs with direct equivalence to English words found them in ASL and/or in invented English-based signed systems used in North America and introduced them in the classroom.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] ASL contains many signs initialised from an alphabet which was also derived from LSF, and Auslan users, already familiar with the related ISL alphabet, accepted many of the new signs easily.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Tertiary education in the US for some deaf Australian adults also accounts for some ASL borrowings found in modern Auslan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Previously, Auslan had been said to be OSV, but more recent scholars have said that this idea is a false-equivalent of Auslan with spoken languages and that using anchor signs is not the same as word order.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] In general, word order in Auslan takes into account context and fluidity between signs being used, being less rigid than many spoken languages.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Rather, Auslan instead follows the clause/word order of TTC—Time, topic, comment.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The frequency of SVO in Auslan may come from code-switching with English (with very high bilingualism for Auslan users), as it is more common with "loan words (signs), English-based idiomatic phrases [and] fingerspelling" as well as by those who learned Auslan later in life.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] In question phrases, the question word must always be at the end in Auslan in open questions.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] This word order is the same for both questions and statements, with questions in Auslan formed by either adding a question word at the end of a clause TOM KICKED PETER WHY or using nonmanual features of a questioning expression.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Verbs in Auslan which are *depicting signs* use head-marking to show the semantic role of the arguments, rather than subject/object.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] An example of this is the word *give*, which involves an actor and a recipient.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Both of these arguments can be expressed on the verb by using signing space.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Verb predicates can be formed by using individual vocabulary words in sequential order (more commonly used by anglophones who speak Auslan as a second language) or using depicting signs, which can "blur" word order, as it allows for multiple signs to be used at once.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] This is generally a mark of high competence and fluency in the language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Lexicalisation of common predicates is common, and compounding is the most common way that new lexical items are produced.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan is a zero-copula language, which means that the verb *to be* is not used at all except when quoting English (in which it is finger-spelt).
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan replaces copula with interrogatives for certain phrase types, sometimes in this context called "rhetorical questions" or "modifiers", using non-manual features to express that it is a statement rather than a question.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The interrogatives of Auslan are more or less direct translations to English ones, with WHY used for this purpose sometimes translated as BECAUSE.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Pronouns are established using the signing space, either arbitrary (for non-present people/things) or iconic.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] For example, "I will give you the doll tomorrow" would be signed as TOMORROW DOLL GIVE, with the sign GIVE starting at the speaker's body and finishing at the receiver's.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The use of signing space also makes all pronouns non-gendered.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] It is sometimes wrongly assumed that English-speaking countries share a single sign language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan is a natural language distinct from spoken or written English.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Its grammar and vocabulary often do not have direct English equivalents and vice versa.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] However, English, as the dominant language in Australia, has had a significant influence on Auslan, especially through manual forms such as fingerspelling and (more recently) Signed English.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] It is difficult to sign Auslan fluently while speaking English, as the word order may be different, and there is often no direct sign-to-word equivalence.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] However, mouthing of an English word together with a sign may serve to clarify when one sign may have several English equivalents.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] In some cases, the mouth gesture that accompanies a sign may not reflect the equivalent translation in English (e.g. a sign meaning "thick" may be accompanied by a mouth gesture that does not resemble any English word).
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] A two-handed manual alphabet, identical to the one used in British Sign Language and New Zealand Sign Language, is integral to Auslan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] This alphabet is used for fingerspelling proper nouns such as personal or place names, common nouns for everyday objects, and English words, especially technical terms, for which there is no widely used sign.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Fingerspelling can also be used for emphasis, clarification, or, sometimes extensively, by English-speaking learners of Auslan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The proportion of fingerspelling versus signs varies with the context and the age of the signer.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] A recent small-scale study puts fingerspelled words in Auslan conversations at about 10% of all lexical items, roughly equal to ASL and higher than many other sign languages, such as New Zealand Sign Language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The proportion is higher in older signers, suggesting that the use of fingerspelling has diminished over time.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Schembri and Johnston (2007) found that the most commonly fingerspelled words in Auslan include "so", "to", "if", "but" and "do".
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Some signs also feature an English word's initial letter as a handshape from a one- or two-handed manual alphabet and use it within a sign.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] For example, part of the sign for "Canberra" incorporates the letter "C".
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Australasian Signed English was created in the late 1970s to represent English words and grammar, using mostly Auslan signs together with some additional contrived signs, as well as borrowings from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] It was used largely in education for teaching English to deaf children or for *discussing* English in academic contexts, and it is not clear to what extent this continues to be the case.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] It was thought to be much easier for hearing teachers and parents to learn another mode of English than to learn a new language with a complex spatial grammar such as Auslan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The use of Signed English in schools is controversial with some in the deaf community who regard Signed English as a contrived and unnatural artificially constructed language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Signed English has now been largely rejected by deaf communities in Australia and its use in education is dwindling; however, a number of its signs have made their way into normal use.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Unlike oral languages, only a minority of deaf children acquire their language from their parents (about 4 or 5% have deaf parents).
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Most acquire Auslan from deaf peers at school or later through deaf community networks.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Many learn Auslan as a "delayed" first language in adolescence or adulthood, after attempting to learn English (or another spoken/written language) without the exposure necessary to properly acquire it.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The deaf community often distinguish between "oral deaf" who grew up in an oral or signed English educational environment without Auslan, and those "*Deaf* Deaf" who learnt Auslan at an early age from deaf parents or at a deaf school.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Regardless of their background, many deaf adults consider Auslan to be their first or primary language, and see themselves as users of English as a second language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan exhibits a high degree of variation, determined by the signer's age, educational background, and regional origin, and the signing community is very accepting of a wide range of individual differences in signing style.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Standard dialects arise through the support of institutions, such as the media, education, government and the law.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] As this support has not existed for most sign languages, coupled with the lack of a widely used written form and communications technologies, Auslan has probably diverged much more rapidly from BSL than Australian English has from British English.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan was introduced to Papua New Guinea, where it mixed with local or home sign and Tok Pisin to produce Papua New Guinean Sign Language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Sign languages related to Auslan also appear to be used in some other parts of the Asia-Pacific, such as in Fiji.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Linguists often regard Auslan as having two major dialects—Northern (Queensland and New South Wales), and Southern (Victoria, Tasmania, South Australia, and Western Australia).
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The vocabulary of the two dialects traditionally differed significantly, with different signs used even for very common concepts such as colours, animals, and days of the week; differences in grammar appear to be slight.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Before schools were established elsewhere, deaf children attended one of these two initial schools, and brought signs back to their own states.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] As schools opened up in each state, new signs also developed in the dormitories and playgrounds of these institutions.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] As a result, Auslan users can identify more precise regional varieties (e.g., "Sydney sign", "Melbourne sign", "Perth sign", "Adelaide sign" and "Brisbane sign"), and even vocabulary that may have been unique to individual schools.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] In a conversation between two strangers, one from Melbourne and the other from Perth, it is likely that one will use a small number of signs unfamiliar to the other, despite both belonging to the same "southern dialect".
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Signers can often identify which school someone went to, even within a few short utterances.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] A number of Indigenous Australian sign languages exist, unrelated to Auslan, such as Warlpiri Sign Language and Yolngu Sign Language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] They occur in the southern, central, and western desert regions, coastal Arnhem Land, some islands of the north coast, the western side of Cape York Peninsula, and on some Torres Strait Islands.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] They have also been noted as far south as the Murray River.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Deaf Indigenous people of Far North Queensland (extending from Yarrabah to Cape York) form a distinct signing community using a dialect of Auslan; it has features of Indigenous sign languages and gestural systems as well as signs and grammar of Auslan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] Auslan has no written form; in the past transcribing Auslan was largely an academic exercise.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] The first Auslan dictionaries used either photographs or drawings with motion arrows to describe signs; more recently, technology has made possible the use of short video clips on CD-ROM or online dictionaries.
[src:a-silent-agreement/auslan] SignWriting, however, has its adherents in Australia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The **Australian Marriage Law Postal Survey** was a national survey by the Australian Government designed to gauge support for legalising same-sex marriage in Australia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The survey was held via the postal service between 12 September and 7 November 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The results of the survey were published on 15 November 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] An additional 36,686 (0.3%) responses were unclear.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The total turnout was 12,727,920 (79.5% of the eligible population).
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Responding to the survey was voluntary, unlike voting in elections and referendums which is compulsory in Australia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Prior to the survey, the Liberal–National Coalition government pledged to facilitate a private member's bill to legalise same-sex marriage in the event of a "Yes" outcome.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Had the survey returned a majority "No" result, the government said it would not allow a vote on such a bill in the House of Representatives.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The *Marriage Amendment (Definition and Religious Freedoms) Act 2017*, which legalised same-sex marriage, was debated and passed by Parliament following publication of the survey results.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The Coalition government allowed its parliamentarians a conscience vote on the legislation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The opposition Australian Labor Party supported the legislation, but exceptionally, also granted its parliamentarians a conscience vote.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Many same-sex marriage proponents were critical of the postal survey, viewing it as a costly delaying tactic and an unnecessary hurdle to a conscience vote on same-sex marriage in the parliament.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The survey was subject to two legal challenges questioning the authority of the ABS to conduct the survey and the government's power to fund the survey from funds designated by law for "urgent" and "unforeseen" circumstances.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Both challenges failed and the High Court of Australia held that the survey was lawful.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Marriage in Australia is the constitutional province of the federal parliament.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Its original legal definition was established by common law as "the union of a man and a woman to the exclusion of all others, voluntarily entered into for life." This definition was codified by the *Marriage Amendment Act 2004*, which inserted it verbatim into the *Marriage Act 1961*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] At the time of the survey, same-sex unions in Australia were treated as de facto unions under federal law.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] These unions provide couples with most, though not all, of the legal rights of marriage, although those rights may be difficult to assert and are not always recognised in practice.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Aside from the legal aspects, de facto relationships do not have the same symbolic significance as marriage.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Before the July 2016 federal election, the Malcolm Turnbull-led Coalition government promised to hold a national vote on same-sex marriage in the form of a compulsory attendance plebiscite.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Opposition to this idea centred on its criticism as an expensive delaying tactic and that it was the duty of the parliament, rather than a matter related to the Australian Constitution.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] While the Coalition won 76 of the 150 seats in the lower house in the 2016 election and managed to form a majority government by one seat, they failed to pass the necessary legislation for a (compulsory attendance) referendum/plebiscite.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The legislation passed the House of Representatives on 20 October 2016 by a vote of 76–67, but was rejected by the Senate on 7 November 2016 by a vote of 33–29.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The idea of a postal plebiscite was originally proposed by Liberal MP Warren Entsch and later endorsed by government ministers Peter Dutton and Mathias Cormann.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Dutton pointed out that a postal vote would not need legislation to operate.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A staffer of Attorney-General George Brandis came up with the idea of a survey as an alternative way to fulfil the government's commitment in mid-July.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] In August 2017, following an attempt by five Liberal Party MPs to change party policy and have a free vote in the parliament on same-sex marriage legislation, the government announced it would move for a voluntary postal survey to be held later that year.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] It stated that the postal vote would only occur in the event the government's (compulsory) referendum/plebiscite legislation was again rejected by the Senate.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] That occurred on 9 August 2017, when a government-initiated motion in the Senate to debate the *Plebiscite (Same-Sex Marriage) Bill 2016* was tied at 31–31; resulting in the motion being defeated.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Following the result in the Senate, the government directed the Australian Statistician (head of the Australian Bureau of Statistics) to begin the process of surveying the views on same-sex marriage of all Australians on the electoral roll.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The government asserted that this proposal did not require legislative approval from the parliament, arguing that the provisions of the *Appropriations Act* and the law governing the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) enabled it to use the ABS for such a purpose.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] This was argued by the government to be similar to the process by which God Save the Queen was replaced by Advance Australia Fair as the Australian national anthem.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The government announced the ABS would be assisted by having staff seconded from the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC), the organisation responsible for elections in Australia and managing the electoral roll.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The cost of the survey to the Australian taxpayer was forecast to be $122 million, however the total amount spent ended up being $80.5 million.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] This expense, as well as the notion that the debate would activate ideological extremists and that normal electoral rules would not apply, were criticised in Parliament.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] By 7 September, the date the high court challenges against the survey were heard, a total of $14.1 million had already been spent by the ABS on the postal survey – $8 million on advertising for the survey, $5.3 million on printing costs, and $600,000 for staff.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The AEC reported that about 68,000 enrolment transactions were completed on 10 August, compared with an average of 4,000 per day.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] In the period 8–14 August over 16,000 people had enrolled, and over 200,000 had updated their details.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] By 20 August, over 36,000 had enrolled, and over 434,000 had updated their enrolment details.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] By 25 August the roll achieved a record high with over 16 million Australians on the roll (an additional 90,000 people had joined with a further 165,000 transactions still to be processed).
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] 65,000 of these new voters are between the ages of 18 and 24.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] With 933,592 enrolment transactions completed by the AEC at the end of processing, more than 98,000 people were added to the roll, and the total number of Australians eligible to participate in the survey was 16,005,998.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] However, after the results of the survey were released, the ABS revealed that in fact 16,006,180 surveys were mailed out to eligible Australians.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The Senate Finance and Public Administration References Committee opened a Public Inquiry into the arrangements around the postal survey on 14 August with a submission made and evidence given by the ABS at hearings on 17 August.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Further hearings involving the ABS, AEC, Australia Post, Department of Finance and Department of Human Services occurred on 7 September and 15 September 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The committee handed down the final report on 13 February 2018.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The results of the survey (including participation rates) were released at a national level, at a state and territory level and at an electorate level.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Two legal challenges were lodged contesting the legality of the survey with the High Court of Australia, both on the grounds of unlawful funding from legally-specified funds and unlawful operation by the ABS.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The first was by same-sex marriage advocates Shelley Argent (national spokeswoman of Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays) and Felicity Marlowe (member of Rainbow Families), along with independent MP Andrew Wilkie.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] They announced they would challenge the postal survey in the High Court on 9 August 2017 and seek a temporary injunction.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The second challenge was by Australian Marriage Equality and Greens Senator Janet Rice.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] An additional complaint was lodged by a 17-year-old boy with the Australian Human Rights Commission in August 2017, on the basis that the rules did not allow provisionally enrolled 16- and 17-year-old Australians the right to participate in the survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Legal counsel to the boy advised that the rejected amendment would make the age discrimination complaint much more difficult to argue, because parliament had considered and rejected extending the vote to enrolled 16- and 17-year-olds.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The High Court pronounced its orders in both cases on 7 September 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The court determined that the survey was lawful, allowing it to proceed as scheduled.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The challengers were ordered to pay costs.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The High Court handed down its unanimous reasons on 28 September 2017, finding that $295 million had been appropriated by parliament, and that whether the expenditure was unforeseen was a matter for the Minister's satisfaction and there was no error of law in either his reasoning or his conclusion.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The information to be collected was "statistical information" of matters prescribed in the *Census and Statistics Regulation* 2016 (Cth).
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] As the court had considered and rejected the grounds of the application, there was no need to decide whether the plaintiffs had standing.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The survey was conducted on a voluntary basis, with no requirement on the part of the eligible Australian to mail back the survey form.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] This led to concerns over a potentially low voter turnout/response rate and the prospect of Indigenous Australians in remote communities being unable to complete a survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Concern had been expressed regarding: electors whose addresses were not visible on the electoral roll (known as silent electors); disenfranchisement in remote communities; Australians overseas; prisoners; non-English speakers; and young people.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Early criticism was also levelled at issues of privacy, with the recent census problems of 2016 being cited.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The ABS advised that survey responses would be anonymous and protected under the secrecy provisions of the Census and Statistics Act 1905.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Prior to the survey commencing, former Privacy Commissioner Malcolm Crompton independently reviewed the ABS's privacy approaches and mitigations and announced he was suitably satisfied.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The ABS also worked to address concerns with special strategies like paperless options (telephony and online form) and form drop off and pick up points in remote and capital city locations.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Additionally, the bureau noted that Australians could also authorise a "trusted person" to complete the survey on their behalf.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] While any person could be appointed a "trusted person", the Chief Minister of the ACT, Andrew Barr offered to fulfil the role for any citizen.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Auditors and an external observer process were established to assure the integrity of the process, though the observers are subject to a lifetime confidentiality agreement.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A quality and integrity report was published by the ABS alongside the release of the survey results.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] During the survey period, online sellers were contacted by the ABS asking them to remove ads by people offering to sell their postal survey or answer.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The ABS advised that such an action would likely constitute an offence under the Census and Statistics Act 1905, the Commonwealth Criminal Code and the survey safeguards legislation passed by Parliament.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The Digital Transformation Agency assisted the ABS with the paperless options for the survey, though due to the compressed timescale of the survey, concerns were anonymously raised by staff that the normal processes were not completed, such as sufficient user testing.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] AWS was brought in on a tender process to assist in the security measures for the online survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A telephone information hotline was established, and received 206,828 calls between 14 August 2017 and 7 November 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Unlike elections or referendums, there were no automatic special regulations relating to advertising requirements or prohibited content for the survey of the kind found in the *Electoral Act*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] On 13 September, the government introduced the *Marriage Law Survey (Additional Safeguards) Bill 2017* for these purposes in the Senate.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The bill passed the Senate, after an amendment moved by Greens leader Richard Di Natale to allow 16- and 17-year-olds the right to participate in the survey was defeated.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The bill immediately proceeded to and was passed by the House of Representatives.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The bill received royal assent on 13 September and went into effect the following day.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The act's provisions automatically expired on 15 November 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Neither the "Yes" or "No" campaign received public funding in the survey, as was envisioned for a compulsory attendance plebiscite.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Prime Minister Turnbull also ruled out a ban on foreign donations for the survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] All Australians whose names are on the electoral roll or had applied to be put on the roll before 24 August 2017 were mailed a survey form and enrolled Australians living overseas along with those in certain special categories were entitled to complete a survey using paperless methods.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The AEC made a statement that provisionally-enrolled 16- and 17-year-olds would not be posted a survey form and an amended direction was later issued by the Government to the Australian Statistician making this clear.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] This direction was subject to a Human Rights Commission complaint by a 17-year-old boy, which was later withdrawn.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] More than 16 million letters were sent from 12 September over almost two weeks (with all delivered by 25 September) and silent electors' packages were sent by the AEC and delivered by the end of September.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] After several "Yes" respondents posted images of their complete forms on social media, the ABS cautioned participants to not photograph their form barcodes, so as to prevent any fraudulent conduct.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Additionally, survey forms could be invalidated in the event the question was rephrased by the participant or the barcode was obscured or removed.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The ABS issued several examples of what constituted a valid and invalid response (such as marking both boxes "Yes" and "No" or crossing out one of the words on the form).
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The ABS advised Australians who received extra survey forms, addressed to the previous occupant who failed to update their electoral details, to write on the front of the envelope "return to sender" and send it back.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] In Australia, it is illegal to open mail addressed to another person.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] In the rare instance of multiple responses being received from an individual, the ABS noted that only the last valid response could expect to be counted.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] On 25 September, the ABS confirmed that all survey forms had been mailed to eligible voters and outlined the process for additional forms to be sent to people who did not receive, lost or spoilt their form.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The ABS also confirmed that a change of mind was not a valid reason for requesting a new form.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Both the "Yes" and "No" campaigns provided 60 observers to the ABS counting process, who examined 606,991 survey results.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Fewer than 500 survey forms were reported as issues to the ABS during the survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] On 28 September, the ABS announced that it would release weekly national estimates of the total number of survey responses received, beginning from 3 October 2017 and ending 7 November.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The primary input to the first three weekly estimates, issued at the National level only, was Australia Post's assessment of the number of containers of sorted envelopes rather than counts of individual forms.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Adjustments were made based on factors such as responses received through other channels and an allowance for forms that are damaged or invalid.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] From the fourth estimate, released on 24 October 2017, the ABS changed the estimation method to use the counts of processed forms.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] This led to an increase in estimated turnout to 74.5% of the population, up 7.0% on the previous week, despite only 300,000 new responses, or 1.9% of the total, being received during that timeframe.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The survey form asked respondents: "Should the law be changed to allow same-sex couples to marry?".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The survey offered two one-word responses: "yes" or "no".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The government did not release a draft bill legalising same-sex marriage prior to the survey, which led to uncertainty over what form legislation would take in the event of a "Yes" verdict.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The wording of an exposure draft of a same-sex marriage bill from early 2017, released by the Attorney-General's office, proposed to amend the definition of "marriage" and replace the terms "man" and "woman" with the gender neutral phrase "two people".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The proposed wording "two people" differed from the wording of the survey question, which referred explicitly to "same-sex couples".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Liberal senator Dean Smith, who drafted a same-sex marriage bill in August 2017, argued his bill struck a "fair balance" in protecting the rights of same-sex couples and the religious freedoms of celebrants.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The bill allows current civil celebrants to become religious celebrants and refuse to perform same sex marriages, and incorporates parts of the Sex Discrimination Act, to allow religious organisations to refuse their services for same-sex marriages.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Smith's bill was formally backed by the Labor Party parliamentary caucus on 17 October 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] However, conservative MPs in the government responded by suggesting up to 100 amendments to the bill may be needed if the "Yes" vote carried.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A rival bill was released on 13 November by Liberal Senator James Paterson, a conservative supporter of same-sex marriage.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The bill contained various protections allowing the refusal of same-sex weddings by anyone who holds a religious or "conscientious belief" against same-sex marriage, including private service providers such as florists and bakers.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Prime Minister Turnbull reacted negatively to Paterson's bill, saying the government "would not countenance" supporting a bill which discriminated against same-sex weddings and that the bill would have "virtually no prospect of getting through the Parliament".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] It was dropped by Senator Paterson within hours of the "Yes" vote being released.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Each of the political parties represented in the Australian Parliament held formalised positions on same-sex marriage and on the merits of the survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The Australian Labor Party formally supported the legalisation of same-sex marriage, though offered its MPs a conscience vote on same-sex marriage legislation until 2019.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The Liberal Party pledged to hold a national vote of some kind before any change to the law, though the party had no official position on the survey question, hence MPs (including Cabinet members) were to free to campaign for either side.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] All politicians were entitled to use their electoral printing and communications budgets in the campaign.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The campaign for supporting voting in favour of same-sex marriage in the survey received support from Labor, the Liberals for yes campaign, and four minor political parties represented in the Federal parliament, and from prominent lobby groups including Australian Marriage Equality and GetUp!.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The campaign advocating voting against changing the marriage laws in the survey was supported by the Nationals and three minor parties represented in the Federal parliament.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Several groups opposed to same-sex marriage, including the Australian Christian Lobby and the Marriage Alliance, formed the Coalition for Marriage to co-ordinate the "No" campaign.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The Liberal Party of Australia did not hold a position either way in the survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Opinion polls in Australia over several years in the lead-up to the survey indicated a comfortable majority of Australians supported same-sex marriage.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A *Guardian* Essential poll conducted just prior to the announcement of the postal survey indicated that 43% approved of a postal vote and 38% disapproved, whereas a week later, 39% approved of the postal survey and 47% disapproved of it.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A small boycott movement existed, although most same sex marriage campaigners who were against a national vote on same-sex marriage urged participation in the postal survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Some informal responses to the survey were intended as a protest vote.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The Government of the Australian Capital Territory and several local governments such as the City of Sydney took official positions supporting the "Yes" campaign.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Public servants in the ACT were warned against campaigning in the survey while in official uniform.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The move to offer official support was criticised by the Liberal Party opposition in the ACT, and similar criticisms lead to the City of Darebin backing down on plans to restrict "No" campaigners from using council facilities.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Several figures and institutions supporting a "No" vote raised the issue of religious freedom during the survey period.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Former Prime Minister John Howard rejected the assurances of Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull and requested that the government explicitly detail proposed religious freedom provisions to potentially be included in same-sex marriage legislation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Likewise several leaders in the Catholic Church raised freedom of religion concerns, citing the case of a Tasmanian archbishop, who was requested to appear at an anti-discrimination commission after having disseminated material supporting a conservative view of marriage.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The veracity of the concerns over religious freedom was disputed heavily in the community.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The divisions extended to the governing Liberal Party, whose president rejected claims that religious freedom could be under threat, in direct contradiction to the party's vice-president, who said that same-sex marriage would have consequences for freedom of speech, religion and association.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Both Prime Minister Turnbull and Bill Shorten, leader of the Opposition, spoke in favour of religious freedom protections, with Turnbull stating he was an even "stronger believer" in freedom of religion than same-sex marriage.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Shorten said the Labor Party would "make sure that concerns about religious freedom are met with and dealt with and are treated with respect".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The prospect of additional religious freedom exemptions being added to existing Australian anti-discrimination law troubled some "Yes" advocates, who feared such provisions could allow service providers to discriminate on any basis, not just limited to couples' sex.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Tiernan Brady described the campaign for religious freedom exemptions as "a blatant attempt to unravel existing anti-discrimination laws which serve everyone in Australia well, not just LGBTI people".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] In response to a Newspoll question on the subject; "Do you think parliament should provide guarantees in law for freedom of conscience, belief and religion if it legislates for same-sex marriage?", 62% responded Yes, 18% responded No and 20% said they were "uncommitted".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] An inquiry into religious freedoms, headed by Philip Ruddock, was announced in November 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] This has been interpreted as a way to allow the speedy passage of the Dean Smith bill and postpone discussions of religious freedom.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] It completed a report on 18 May 2018, which was not publicly released until 13 December 2018, although the recommendations were leaked to Fairfax Media in October 2018.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The government responded by proposing a religious discrimination act.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Advertising by both sides was extensive for much of the survey period.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The first television ad for the "No" campaign, revealed shortly after the campaign began, featured three women and focused on the Safe Schools education program.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The "Yes" campaign promptly aired a rebuttal by Dr.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A "No" supporter funded the skywritten message "Vote No" over Sydney in September, which was defended by Turnbull as an expression of free speech.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] In Melbourne, a giant "NO" was written in the sky in response to the survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Subsequent "Yes" ads focused heavily on a concerted "get out the vote" effort, and featured high-profile figures such as Ian Thorpe and others posting their surveys, as well as a themed ad screened during the finale of popular television show *The Bachelor*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The "Yes" campaign were also responsible for a widespread SMS message to many Australian mobile phones which lead to some complaints over how people's numbers were obtained, however the campaign advised the numbers were generated through random dialling technology previously used in elections.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Both of the "No" campaign's next most prominent advertisements concentrated mostly on the notion of gender theory in school curriculum, one such ad focusing on the book The Gender Fairy and featuring two of the mothers from the original advertisement.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] As of mid-September, prominent "No" campaigner Lyle Shelton was mentioned across news outlets more times than the leading three "Yes" campaigners, Alex Greenwich, Tiernan Brady and Sally Rugg, combined.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Legislation in effect for the duration of the survey made it illegal to vilify, intimidate, threaten or harm "on the basis of sexual orientation, gender identity, intersex status or religion", with a fine of up to $12,600 for breaches.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Furthermore, all campaign material was required to be properly authorised.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] By 26 September, marketing services group Ebiquity estimated that the lead "No" group (Coalition for Marriage) had spent about $3,975,872 on advertising, a figure higher than their estimate for the two lead "Yes" groups (Australian Marriage Equality and the Equality Campaign), about $2,920,740.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Two donations of note were made in the course of the survey; $1 million was personally donated by Qantas CEO Alan Joyce to the "Yes" campaign, and $1 million was donated by the Anglican Diocese of Sydney to the "No" campaign.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Former Prime Minister Tony Abbott said in November that the "No" campaign had 20,000 donors who donated around $6 million to the campaign.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] At the 2017 NRL Grand Final, American rapper Macklemore was booked to perform several songs, including "Same Love".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The song topped the Australian charts in 2013, and was regarded as an anthem for same-sex marriage advocates during the campaign in Macklemore's home state of Washington.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] In the days leading up to the grand final, the single returned to the top of the Australian iTunes charts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Several prominent conservative politicians voiced strong opposition to the scheduled performance of "Same Love", given its high-profile support for the "Yes" campaign during the voting period of the Australian Marriage Law Postal Survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Macklemore acknowledged the controversy several days before the final, but vowed to "go harder" as a result.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A nationwide study of lesbian, gay, and bisexual mental health found that increased exposure to negative, anti-LGBT media messages during the postal survey was related to increased levels of depressions, anxiety, and stress.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The rights and welfare of children, particularly as it related to same-sex parenting, was occasionally discussed publicly through the survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Organisations such as the Australian Catholic Bishops' Conference, the Presbyterian Church of Australia and the Australian National Imams Council all advocated strongly for nuclear family structures during the survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A fact check article published in *The Conversation*, which was based on a review of the literature on outcomes for children of same-sex parents, showed equal or better outcomes for children raised by parents of the same gender.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Likewise, a review published late in the survey period by the Medical Journal of Australia agreed with *The Conversation's* findings, but noted that the effects of being exposed to stigma and discrimination could lead to poorer public health outcomes for the children in same-sex parented families.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] A number of helplines, counselling services and mental health strategies were made available to LGBTIQ people by several organisations, including the Australian Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Similar services were available for Defence, Victorian local councils and health services such as Alfred Health.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] State governments in Western Australia, Victoria and Queensland all allocated additional funds, ranging from $60,000 to $500,000, to LGBTIQ mental health services.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The survey period was associated with increases in the number of LGBTIQ people requesting assistance for mental health issues.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Reach Out Australia, which lead the pro-same-sex marriage campaign by five mental health services, reported increases (variously at) 20, 30 and 40 per cent in clients during the survey period and crisis support service Lifeline noted a spike in calls about the impact of the survey.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Mental health surveys conducted during this period showed that increased exposure to the 'no' campaign was related to increased levels of depression, anxiety, and stress among same-sex attracted Australians.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Shorten wrote to Turnbull about increasing the funding for mental health services during the survey from the federal budget, but did not receive a response.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The survey was accompanied by a variety of acts of vandalism and abuse by both parties.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] In September, a banner reading "Burn Churches, Not Queers" was unfurled at a Coalition for Marriage meeting, and in October several churches in Victoria and New South Wales were graffitied with messages criticising "No" voters.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] Similarly, a passenger train on the Sydney Trains network was vandalised with messages encouraging "No" votes, including foul language and the Nazi swastika.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p01] The ABC created a digital news service designed to track incidents of violence and abuse throughout the survey, with both "Yes" and "No" voters/organisations being targeted on occasions.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The Australian Capital Territory recorded the strongest "Yes" vote at 74% while New South Wales had the lowest level of support at 57.8%.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] All other jurisdictions had above 60% support, with Victoria the leading state on 64.9% support.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] A majority of survey participants returned affirmative responses in 133 electorates.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The 17 electorates with majority negative responses were predominantly in Western Sydney (12 electorates), as well as rural Queensland (three electorates) and outer suburban Melbourne (two electorates).
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Defying a national trend, in New South Wales, country participants were more likely to vote yes than their city counterparts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Most electorates either swung heavily in favour or against same sex marriage.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] There were only 25 electorates in which the result was between 45 and 55 per cent.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] In contrast, 41 electorates at the 2016 Australian federal election had two party preferred results within the same degree of margin (±5 per cent).
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] At the 2013 election, 49 electorates were as approximately close.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The heavy concentration of negative responses in working-class, multicultural Western Sydney led to speculation about the underlying economic and demographic factors leading to the result.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] *The Guardian* noted that the portion of persons holding religious beliefs in an electorate was one of the strongest factors, calculating a −0.8 correlation between religion and responding affirmatively.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Islam, followed by Oriental Orthodox and Catholicism were the strongest predictors of negative responses.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Affirmative responses were correlated to income and education, and to a lesser extent, being born in Australia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] There was a higher percentage of responses to the survey from 18 and 19-year olds than any other age group under 45, despite concerns during the survey period that this group would be disenfranchised.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Several hours after the results of the survey were released, Senator Dean Smith introduced the *Marriage Amendment (Definition and Religious Freedoms) Bill 2017* into the Australian Senate.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The bill amended the definition of "marriage" in the *Marriage Act* to recognise a "union of 2 people", which would enable same-sex marriage.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The bill drafted by Liberal Senator James Paterson, which would have extended further protections and exemptions for people opposed to same-sex marriage was dropped, with the Senator and several conservative MPs instead deciding to offer amendments to the Smith bill during parliamentary debate.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] There was some unresolved disagreement by politicians who advocated for a "No" result as to whether further religious protections should be added to the Smith bill as an amendment at this time or whether a later bill for this purpose should be considered.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The bill passed the Senate by 43 votes to 12 on 29 November 2017, with none of the amendments providing further protections and exemptions being accepted.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Openly gay MP and same-sex marriage advocate Tim Wilson proposed in Parliament to his partner, Ryan Bolger, who was in the public gallery.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] It was the first known engagement on the floor of the House of Representatives.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The bill passed the House of Representatives without amendment on 7 December 2017.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] It received royal assent on 8 December 2017 and came into effect the following day.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Existing same-sex marriages performed outside Australia were recognized from 9 December, while new marriages required one month's notice, and so began from 9 January 2018.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Several couples successfully applied for an exemption from the notice period, and the first legal same-sex wedding under Australian law was held on 15 December 2017, with further weddings occurring the following day.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The survey revealed differences between the views of some MPs and the majority of their constituents on this issue.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Several Labor MPs in Western Sydney electorates recommitted to voting in favour of same-sex marriage legislation, despite majority "No" votes among their constituents.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Labor Senator Sam Dastyari acknowledged this issue, noting there was a "huge disconnect" of views on same-sex marriage within traditionally Labor-held seats in Western Sydney.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Similarly, several Liberal MPs and Senators said they would vote "No" irrespective of the result in their electorate or state.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Alex Greenwich of the "Yes" campaign stated the survey results represented a level of "unprecedented support and momentum [that] has exceeded the expectations, not just of this campaign, but any campaign in our history".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Spokesperson for the "No" campaign and the Coalition for Marriage, Lyle Shelton said it was a disappointing result, but he accepted and respected the verdict of the people.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Tony Abbott said the Parliament should "respect the result".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Speaking immediately after the survey results were released, Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull called the outcome "overwhelming" and recommitted to passing same-sex marriage legislation in the Parliament before Christmas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Opposition Leader Bill Shorten shared that commitment and called on conservative MPs in the government to respect the will of the people and not attempt any delaying tactics in the parliament.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The verdict announcement was watched and celebrated by tens of thousands of "Yes" supporters in capital cities.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] In Melbourne, several thousand people gathered outside the State Library of Victoria to watch the results before celebrations began in Melbourne's Lygon Street that evening.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The huge "Yes" vote in Victoria prompted Premier Daniel Andrews to label the result reflective of Victoria's reputation as "the most progressive state" in the nation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] A large crowd also descended on Prince Alfred Park in Sydney for the announcement, which included high-profile figures Magda Szubanski and Ian Thorpe in attendance.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Reflecting on the atmosphere in Sydney, local newspaper *The Sydney Morning Herald* claimed the results reflected "a momentous civil rights milestone" for Australia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Smaller crowds also gathered in several locations in Canberra, Adelaide and Perth to celebrate the result.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] In Canberra (capital city of the Australian Capital Territory, the jurisdiction with the highest "Yes" vote in the country), the results were celebrated festively into the night, as thousands of people forced the closure of Lonsdale Street in the city.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Labor Party Senator Penny Wong's appearance onstage at the event "drew thunderous applause from a crowd of thousands".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The results were welcomed by many representatives of Australia's business community.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Among the highest profile of them was Qantas CEO Alan Joyce, who called it "an amazing outcome and we should all be very proud of this amazing country", an observation shared by leaders of corporate bodies Telstra and ANZ Bank.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Businesses related to the wedding industry, such as florists, bakers and others were poised to reap the benefit of what some projected to be a multi-billion dollar boost to the industry over the following 12 months.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The social media coverage of the results announcement was so immense that, with more than 4000 tweets sent every second during the peak of the day, the survey results trend was more than 10 times as popular as Australia's "race that stops the nation", the Melbourne Cup.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] In celebration of the "Yes" vote, a Sydney-based visual artist painted a large, "light-hearted mural" on the wall of the Botany View Hotel, Newtown, depicting Tony Abbott with his hand down the pants of Cardinal George Pell.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The mural was later defaced and painted over in black paint.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The visual artist said he planned to leave the defaced mural as it was, stating "when you're making public art, the reaction is important, the reaction is needed".
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] These sentiments were shared by the leaders of the Anglican Church of Australia.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Reflecting on the heavily concentrated "No" vote prominent in Western Sydney electorates, Keysar Trad, former president of the Australian Federation of Islamic Councils, labelled it "heartening" and praised the role of faith leaders in both the Muslim and Christian communities in the region.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Being born overseas has been noted to correlate with a "No" response and religious belief to correlate even more strongly.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Social progressives received criticism for allegedly ignoring the "No" vote among Islamic communities, though a Guardian blog argued that religion was connected with the "No" vote.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] World leaders to congratulate Australia for the result included Nicola Sturgeon (First Minister of Scotland), Justin Trudeau (Prime Minister of Canada) and Theresa May (Prime Minister of the United Kingdom).
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The survey ran more than $40 million under its projected budget of $122 million.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Greens leader Richard Di Natale wrote to the Prime Minister requesting that some of the unused funds be redirected to mental health and other support services for LGBT Australians hurt by the campaign.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The survey added $26.3 million in revenue to Australia Post.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] A 2019 University of Sydney study found that the same-sex marriage debate led to elevated psychological distress for lesbian, gay, and bisexual people during the survey period, including increased levels of depression, anxiety and stress.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] The research also found that same-sex attracted Australians benefitted from public displays of support from family and friends, which increased their resilience during the process.
[src:a-silent-agreement/australian-marriage-law-postal-survey-p02] Another 2019 study conducted for the Australia Institute similarly found that "the marriage equality debate represented an acute external minority stress event that had measurable negative impacts on mental health of LGBTIQ people and their allies".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The traditional Christmas narrative recounted in the New Testament, known as the Nativity of Jesus, says that Jesus was born in Bethlehem, in accordance with messianic prophecies.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] When Joseph and Mary arrived in the city, the inn had no room, and so they were offered a stable where the Christ Child was soon born, with angels proclaiming this news to shepherds, who then spread the word.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] There are different hypotheses regarding the date of the birth of Jesus.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In the early fourth century, the church fixed the date as December 25, the date of the winter solstice in the Roman Empire.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] It is nine months after Annunciation on March 25, also the Roman date of the spring equinox.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Most Christians celebrate on December 25 in the Gregorian calendar, which has been adopted almost universally in the civil calendars used in countries throughout the world.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] However, part of the Eastern Christian Churches celebrate Christmas on December 25 of the older Julian calendar, which currently corresponds to January 7 in the Gregorian calendar.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] For Christians, celebrating that God came into the world in the form of man to atone for the sins of humanity is more important than knowing Jesus Christ's exact birth date.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The customs associated with Christmas in various countries have a mix of pre-Christian, Christian, and secular themes and origins.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Additionally, several related and often interchangeable figures, known as Santa Claus, Father Christmas, Saint Nicholas, and Christkind, are associated with bringing gifts to children during the Christmas season and have their own body of traditions and lore.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Because gift-giving and many other aspects of the Christmas festival involve heightened economic activity, Christmas has become a significant event and a key sales period for retailers and businesses.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Over the past few centuries, Christmas has had a steadily growing economic effect in many regions of the world.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The English word *Christmas* is a shortened form of 'Christ's Mass'.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The word is recorded as *Crīstesmæsse* in 1038 and *Cristes-messe* in 1131.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] *Crīst* (genitive *Crīstes*) is from the Koine Greek Χριστός (*Khrīstos*, 'Christ'), a translation of the Hebrew מָשִׁיחַ‎ (*Māšîaḥ*, 'Messiah'), meaning 'anointed'; and *mæsse* is from the Latin *missa*, the celebration of the Eucharist.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The form *Christenmas* was also used during some periods, but is now considered archaic.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The term derives from Middle English *Cristenmasse*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] *Xmas* is an abbreviation of *Christmas*, particularly in print, based on the initial letter chi (Χ) in the Greek Χριστός (Christ), although some style guides discourage its use.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] This abbreviation has a precedent in Middle English *Χρ̄es masse* (where *Χρ̄* is another abbreviation of the Greek word).
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The Anglo-Saxons referred to Christmas as *midwinter*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The period corresponding to December and January was called *Gēola* ('Yule'), and this term was eventually equated with Christmastide; Old English *Ġeōhel-dæg* ('Yule Day') was sometimes used as a name for Christmas Day.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] *Yule* or *Yuil* survived as the main name for Christmastide in Scotland until the modern era.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] A rare name for Christmas in Old English was *Nātiuiteð* ('Nativity'), from the Latin *nātīvitās* meaning 'birth'.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] 'Noel' (also 'Nowel' or 'Nowell', as in "The First Nowell") entered English in the late 14th century and is from the Old French *noël* or *naël*, itself ultimately from the Latin *nātālis (diēs)* meaning 'birth (day)'.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] During the late Qing dynasty, the *Shanghai News* referred to Christmas by a variety of terms.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In 1872, it initially called Christmas "Jesus' birthday" (Chinese: 耶穌誕日; pinyin: *yēsū dànrì*).
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] This term was gradually replaced by the now standard term "Festival of the birth of the Holy One" (Chinese: 聖誕節; pinyin: *shèngdàn jiē*) during the early twentieth century.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The gospels of Luke and Matthew describe Jesus as being born in Bethlehem of Judea to the Virgin Mary.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In the Gospel of Luke, Joseph and Mary travel from Nazareth to Bethlehem in order to be counted for a census, and Jesus is born there and placed in a manger.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Angels proclaim him a savior for all people, and three shepherds come to adore him.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In the Gospel of Matthew, by contrast, three magi follow a star to Bethlehem to bring gifts to Jesus.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In the 2nd century, the "earliest church records" indicate that "Christians were remembering and celebrating the birth of the Lord", an "observance [that] sprang up organically from the authentic devotion of ordinary believers"; although "they did not agree upon a set date".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Though Christmas did not appear on the lists of festivals given by the early Christian writers Irenaeus and Tertullian, the early Church Fathers John Chrysostom, Augustine of Hippo, and Jerome attested to December 25 as the date of Christmas toward the end of the fourth century.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The earliest document to place Jesus's birthday on December 25 is the Chronograph of 354 (also called the Calendar of Filocalus), which also names it as the birthday of the god Sol Invictus (the 'Invincible Sun').
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Liturgical historians generally agree that this part of the text was written in Rome in AD 336.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] This is consistent with the assertion that the date was formally set by Pope Julius I, bishop of Rome from 337 to 352.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] December 25 was the traditional date of the winter solstice in the Roman Empire, where most Christians lived, and the Roman festival *Dies Natalis Solis Invicti* (birthday of Sol Invictus) had been held on this date since AD 274.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In the East, the birth of Jesus was celebrated in connection with the Epiphany on January 6.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] This holiday was not primarily about Christ's birth, but rather his baptism.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Christmas was promoted in the East as part of the revival of Orthodox Christianity that followed the death of the pro-Arian Emperor Valens at the Battle of Adrianople in 378.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The feast was introduced in Constantinople in 379, in Antioch by John Chrysostom towards the end of the fourth century, probably in 388, and in Alexandria in the following century.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] There is evidence that Christmas was celebrated in Jerusalem by the sixth century.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In the Early Middle Ages, Christmas Day was overshadowed by Epiphany, which in western Christianity focused on the visit of the magi.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] However, the medieval calendar was dominated by Christmas-related holidays.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The forty days before Christmas became the "forty days of St.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Martin" (which began on November 11, the feast of St.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In Italy, former Saturnalian traditions were attached to Advent.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Around the 12th century, these traditions transferred again to the Twelve Days of Christmas (December 25 – January 5); a time that appears in the liturgical calendars as Christmastide or Twelve Holy Days.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In 567, the Council of Tours put in place the season of Christmastide, proclaiming "the twelve days from Christmas to Epiphany as a sacred and festive season, and established the duty of Advent fasting in preparation for the feast".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] This was done in order to solve the "administrative problem for the Roman Empire as it tried to coordinate the solar Julian calendar with the lunar calendars of its provinces in the east".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The prominence of Christmas Day increased gradually after Charlemagne was crowned Emperor on Christmas Day in 800.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] King Edmund the Martyr was anointed on Christmas in 855 and King William I of England was crowned on Christmas Day 1066.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] By the High Middle Ages, the holiday had become so prominent that chroniclers routinely noted where various magnates celebrated Christmas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] King Richard II of England hosted a Christmas feast in 1377 at which 28 oxen and 300 sheep were eaten.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The Yule boar was a common feature of medieval Christmas feasts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Caroling also became popular, and was originally performed by a group of dancers who sang.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The group was composed of a lead singer and a ring of dancers that provided the chorus.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Writers of the time condemned caroling as lewd, indicating that the unruly traditions of Saturnalia and Yule may have continued in this form.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] "Misrule"—drunkenness, promiscuity, gambling—was also an important aspect of the festival.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In England, gifts were exchanged on New Year's Day (a custom at the royal court), and there was special Christmas ale.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Christmas during the Middle Ages was a public festival that incorporated ivy, holly, and other evergreens.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Christmas gift-giving during the Middle Ages was usually between people with legal relationships, such as tenant and landlord.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The annual indulgence in eating, dancing, singing, sporting, and card playing escalated in England, and by the 17th century the Christmas season featured lavish dinners, elaborate masques, and pageants.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In 1607, King James I insisted that a play be acted on Christmas night and that the court indulge in games.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] It was during the Reformation in 16th–17th-century Europe that many Protestants changed the gift bringer to the Christ Child or *Christkindl*, and the date of giving gifts changed from December 6 to Christmas Eve.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Following the Protestant Reformation, many of the new denominations, including the Anglican Church and Lutheran Church, continued to celebrate Christmas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In 1629, the Anglican poet John Milton penned *On the Morning of Christ's Nativity*, a poem that has since been read by many during Christmastide.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Donald Heinz, a professor at California State University, Chico, states that Martin Luther "inaugurated a period in which Germany would produce a unique culture of Christmas, much copied in North America".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Among the congregations of the Dutch Reformed Church, Christmas was celebrated as one of the principal evangelical feasts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] However, in 17th century England, some groups such as the Puritans strongly condemned the celebration of Christmas, considering it a Catholic invention and the "trappings of popery" or the "rags of the Beast".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In contrast, the established Anglican Church "pressed for a more elaborate observance of feasts, penitential seasons, and saints' days.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The calendar reform became a major point of tension between the Anglican party and the Puritan party".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The Catholic Church also responded, promoting the festival in a more religiously oriented form.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] King Charles I of England directed his noblemen and gentry to return to their landed estates in midwinter to keep up their old-style Christmas generosity.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Following the Parliamentarian victory over Charles I during the English Civil War, England's Puritan rulers banned Christmas in 1647.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Oliver Cromwell even ordered his troops to confiscate any special meals made on Christmas Day.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Protests followed as pro-Christmas rioting broke out in several cities and for weeks Canterbury was controlled by the rioters, who decorated doorways with holly and shouted royalist slogans.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Football, among the sports the Puritans banned on a Sunday, was also used as a rebellious force: when Puritans outlawed Christmas in England in December 1647 the crowd brought out footballs as a symbol of festive misrule.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The book, *The Vindication of Christmas* (London, 1652), argued against the Puritans, and makes note of Old English Christmas traditions, dinner, roast apples on the fire, card playing, dances with "plow-boys" and "maidservants", old Father Christmas and carol singing.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] During the ban, semi-clandestine religious services marking Christ's birth continued to be held, and people sang carols in secret.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Christmas was restored as a legal holiday in England with the Restoration of King Charles II in 1660 when Puritan legislation was declared void, with Christmas again freely celebrated in England.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Many Calvinist clergymen disapproved of Christmas celebrations.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] As such, in Scotland, the Presbyterian Church of Scotland discouraged the observance of Christmas, and though James VI commanded its celebration in 1618, attendance at church was scant.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The Parliament of Scotland officially abolished the observance of Christmas in 1640, claiming that the church had been "purged of all superstitious observation of days".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Whereas in England, Wales and Ireland Christmas Day is a common law holiday, having been a customary holiday since time immemorial, it was not until 1871 that it was designated a bank holiday in Scotland.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The diary of James Woodforde, from the latter half of the 18th century, details the observance of Christmas and celebrations associated with the season over a number of years.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] As in England, Puritans in Colonial America staunchly opposed the observation of Christmas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The Pilgrims of New England pointedly spent their first December 25 in the New World working normally.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Puritans such as Cotton Mather condemned Christmas both because scripture did not mention its observance and because Christmas celebrations of the day often involved boisterous behavior.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Many non-Puritans in New England deplored the loss of the holidays enjoyed by the laboring classes in England.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Christmas observance was outlawed in Boston in 1659.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The ban on Christmas observance was revoked in 1681 by English governor Edmund Andros, but it was not until the mid-19th century that celebrating Christmas became fashionable in the Boston region.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] At the same time, Christian residents of Virginia and New York observed the holiday freely.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Pennsylvania Dutch settlers, predominantly Moravian settlers of Bethlehem, Nazareth, and Lititz in Pennsylvania and the Wachovia settlements in North Carolina, were enthusiastic celebrators of Christmas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The Moravians in Bethlehem had the first Christmas trees in America as well as the first Nativity Scenes.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Christmas fell out of favor in the United States after the American Revolution, when it was considered an English custom.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] With the atheistic Cult of Reason in power during the era of Revolutionary France, Christian Christmas religious services were banned and the three kings cake was renamed the "equality cake" under anticlerical government policies.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In the early-19th century, writers imagined Tudor-period Christmas as a time of heartfelt celebration.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Its instant popularity played a major role in portraying Christmas as a holiday emphasizing family, goodwill, and compassion.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Dickens sought to construct Christmas as a family-centered festival of generosity, linking "worship and feasting, within a context of social reconciliation".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Superimposing his humanitarian vision of the holiday, in what has been termed "Carol Philosophy", Dickens influenced many aspects of Christmas that are celebrated today in Western culture, such as family gatherings, seasonal food and drink, dancing, games, and a festive generosity of spirit.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] It has been said that Dickens' breakthrough with *A Christmas Carol* was his "ingenious pairing of seasonal fiction and seasonal [book] sales." A prominent phrase from the tale, "Merry Christmas", was popularized following the appearance of the story.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] This coincided with the appearance of the Oxford Movement and the growth of Anglo-Catholicism, which led a revival in traditional rituals and religious observances.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The term *Scrooge* became a synonym for miser, with the phrase "Bah!
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Humbug!" becoming emblematic of a dismissive attitude of the festive spirit.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In 1843, the first commercial Christmas card was produced by Sir Henry Cole.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The revival of the Christmas Carol began with William Sandys's *Christmas Carols Ancient and Modern* (1833), with the first appearance in print of "The First Noel", "I Saw Three Ships", "Hark the Herald Angels Sing" and "God Rest Ye Merry, Gentlemen", popularized in Dickens's *A Christmas Carol*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In Britain, the Christmas tree was introduced in the early 19th century by the German-born Queen Charlotte.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In 1832, the future Queen Victoria wrote about her delight at having a Christmas tree, hung with lights, ornaments, and presents placed round it.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] After her marriage to her German cousin Prince Albert, by 1841 the custom became more widespread throughout Britain.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] An image of the British royal family with their Christmas tree at Windsor Castle created a sensation when it was published in the *Illustrated London News* in 1848.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] A modified version of this image was published in *Godey's Lady's Book*, Philadelphia in 1850.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] By the 1870s, putting up a Christmas tree had become common in America.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In America, interest in Christmas had been revived in the 1820s by several short stories by Washington Irving which appear in his *The Sketch Book of Geoffrey Crayon, Gent.* and "Old Christmas".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In 1822, Clement Clarke Moore wrote the poem *A Visit From St.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Nicholas* (popularly known by its first line: *Twas the Night Before Christmas*).
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The poem helped popularize the tradition of exchanging gifts, and seasonal Christmas shopping began to assume economic importance.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] This also started the cultural conflict between the holiday's spiritual significance and its associated commercialism that some see as corrupting the holiday.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In her 1850 book *The First Christmas in New England*, Harriet Beecher Stowe includes a character who complains that the true meaning of Christmas was lost in a shopping spree.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] While the celebration of Christmas was not yet customary in some regions in the U.S., Henry Wadsworth Longfellow detected "a transition state about Christmas here in New England" in 1856.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] "The old puritan feeling prevents it from being a cheerful, hearty holiday; though every year makes it more so".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The First Congregational Church of Rockford, Illinois, "although of genuine Puritan stock", was 'preparing for a grand Christmas jubilee', a news correspondent reported in 1864.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] By 1860, fourteen states including several from New England had adopted Christmas as a legal holiday.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In 1875, Louis Prang introduced the Christmas card to Americans.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] He has been called the "father of the American Christmas card".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] On June 28, 1870, Christmas was formally declared a United States federal holiday.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] During the First World War and particularly in 1914, a series of informal truces took place for Christmas between opposing armies.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] The truces, which were organised spontaneously by fighting men, ranged from promises not to shoot (shouted at a distance in order to ease the pressure of war for the day) to friendly socializing, gift giving and even sport between enemies.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] These incidents became a well known and semi-mythologised part of popular memory.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] They have been described as a symbol of common humanity even in the darkest of situations and used to demonstrate to children the ideals of Christmas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Under the state atheism of the Soviet Union, after its foundation in 1917, Christmas celebrations—along with other Christian holidays—were prohibited in public.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] At the height of this persecution, in 1929, on Christmas Day, children in Moscow were encouraged to spit on crucifixes as a protest against the holiday.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Instead, the importance of the holiday and all its trappings, such as the Christmas tree and gift-giving, was transferred to the New Year.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] It was not until the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 that the persecution ended and Orthodox Christmas became a state holiday again for the first time in Russia after seven decades.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In 1991, the Gubbio Christmas Tree, in Italy, 650 metres (2,130 ft) high and decorated with over 700 lights, entered the Guinness Book of Records as the tallest Christmas tree in the world.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] In the U.S., and Canada, where the use of the term "Holidays" is most prevalent, opponents of its usage have denounced what they perceive to be avoidance of using the term "Christmas" as being politically correct.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] Some right-wing Christian organizations, such as Pat Robertson's American Center for Law and Justice, cite these alleged "attacks" on Christmas as constituting a "War on Christmas", a term largely popularized by conservative commentator Bill O'Reilly.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p01] However "Happy Holidays" has been commonly used in the US for over 100 years.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas Day is celebrated as a major festival and public holiday in countries around the world, including many whose populations are mostly non-Christian.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In some non-Christian areas, periods of former colonial rule introduced the celebration (e.g.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Hong Kong); in others, Christian minorities or foreign cultural influences have led populations to observe the holiday.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Countries such as Japan, where Christmas is popular despite there being only a small number of Christians, have adopted many of the cultural aspects of Christmas, such as gift-giving, decorations, and Christmas trees.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] A similar example is in Turkey, being Muslim-majority and with a small number of Christians, where Christmas trees and decorations tend to line public streets during the festival.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The prevailing atmosphere of Christmas has also continually evolved since the holiday's inception, ranging from a sometimes raucous, drunken, carnival-like state in the Middle Ages, to a tamer family-oriented and children-centered theme introduced in a 19th-century transformation.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The celebration of Christmas was banned on more than one occasion within certain groups, such as the Puritans and Jehovah's Witnesses (who do not celebrate birthdays in general), due to concerns that it was too unbiblical.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Celtic winter herbs such as mistletoe and ivy, and the custom of kissing under a mistletoe, are common in modern Christmas celebrations in the English-speaking countries.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The pre-Christian Germanic peoples—including the Anglo-Saxons and the Norse—celebrated a winter festival called Yule, held in the late December to early January period, yielding modern English *yule*, today used as a synonym for *Christmas*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In Germanic language-speaking areas, numerous elements of modern Christmas folk custom and iconography may have originated from Yule, including the Yule log, Yule boar, and the Yule goat.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Often leading a ghostly procession through the sky (the Wild Hunt), the long-bearded god Odin is referred to as "the Yule one" and "Yule father" in Old Norse texts, while other gods are referred to as "Yule beings".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] On the other hand, as there are no reliable existing references to a Christmas log prior to the 16th century, the burning of the Christmas block may have been an early modern invention by Christians unrelated to the pagan practice.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Among countries with a strong Christian tradition, a variety of Christmas celebrations have developed that incorporate regional and local cultures.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] For example, in eastern Europe Christmas celebrations incorporated pre-Christian traditions such as the Koleda, which shares parallels with the Christmas carol.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas Day (inclusive of its vigil, Christmas Eve), is a Festival in the Lutheran Churches, a solemnity in the Roman Catholic Church, and a Principal Feast of the Anglican Communion.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Other Christian denominations do not rank their feast days but nevertheless place importance on Christmas Eve/Christmas Day, as with other Christian feasts like Easter, Ascension Day, and Pentecost.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] As such, for Christians, attending a Christmas Eve or Christmas Day church service plays an important part in the recognition of the Christmas season.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas, along with Easter, is the period of the highest annual church attendance.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] A 2010 survey by LifeWay Christian Resources found that six in ten Americans attend church services during this time.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the United Kingdom, the Church of England reported an estimated attendance of 2.5 million people at Christmas services in 2015.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Nativity scenes are known from 10th-century Rome.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] They were popularised by Saint Francis of Assisi from 1223, quickly spreading across Europe.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In certain parts of the world, notably Sicily, living nativity scenes following the tradition of Saint Francis are a popular alternative to static crèches.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The first commercially produced decorations appeared in Germany in the 1860s, inspired by paper chains made by children.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In countries where a representation of the Nativity scene is very popular, people are encouraged to compete and create the most original or realistic ones.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Within some families, the pieces used to make the representation are considered a valuable family heirloom.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The traditional colours of Christmas decorations are red, green, and gold.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Red symbolizes the blood of Jesus, which was shed in his crucifixion; green symbolizes eternal life, and in particular the evergreen tree, which does not lose its leaves in the winter; and gold is the first colour associated with Christmas, as one of the three gifts of the Magi, symbolizing royalty.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The Christmas tree was first used by German Lutherans in the 16th century, with records indicating that a Christmas tree was placed in the Cathedral of Strassburg in 1539, under the leadership of the Protestant Reformer, Martin Bucer.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the United States, these "German Lutherans brought the decorated Christmas tree with them; the Moravians put lighted candles on those trees".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] When decorating the Christmas tree, many individuals place a star at the top of the tree symbolizing the Star of Bethlehem, a fact recorded by *The School Journal* in 1897.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Professor David Albert Jones of Oxford University writes that in the 19th century, it became popular for people to also use an angel to top the Christmas tree in order to symbolize the angels mentioned in the accounts of the Nativity of Jesus.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Additionally, in the context of a Christian celebration of Christmas, the Christmas tree, being evergreen in colour, is symbolic of Christ, who offers eternal life; the candles or lights on the tree represent the Light of the World—Jesus—born in Bethlehem.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christian services for family use and public worship have been published for the blessing of a Christmas tree, after it has been erected.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The English language phrase "Christmas tree" is first recorded in 1835 and represents an importation from the German language.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Since the 16th century, the poinsettia, a native plant from Mexico, has been associated with Christmas carrying the Christian symbolism of the Star of Bethlehem; in that country it is known in Spanish as the *Flower of the Holy Night*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Other popular holiday plants include holly, mistletoe, red amaryllis, and Christmas cactus.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Along with a Christmas tree, the interior of a home may be decorated with these plants, along with garlands and evergreen foliage.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The display of Christmas villages has also become a tradition in many homes this season.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The outside of houses may be decorated with lights and sometimes with illuminated Christmas figures.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Mistletoe features prominently in European myth and folklore (for example, the legend of Baldr).
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] It is customary to hang a sprig of mistletoe in the house at Christmas, and anyone standing underneath it may be kissed.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Other traditional decorations include bells, candles, candy canes, stockings, wreaths, and angels.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The wreaths and candles in each window are a more traditional Christmas display.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The concentric assortment of leaves, usually from an evergreen, make up Christmas wreaths.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Candles in each window are meant to demonstrate that Christians believe that Jesus Christ is the ultimate light of the world.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas lights and banners may be hung along streets, music played by speakers, and Christmas trees placed in prominent places.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] It is common in many parts of the world for town squares and consumer shopping areas to sponsor and display decorations.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Rolls of brightly colored paper with secular or religious Christmas motifs are manufactured to wrap gifts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In some countries, Christmas decorations are traditionally taken down on Twelfth Night.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The tradition of the Nativity scene comes from Italy.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] One of the earliest representation in art of the nativity was found in the early Christian Roman catacomb of Saint Valentine.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Another, of similar date, is beneath the pulpit in Sant'Ambrogio, Milan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] For the Christian celebration of Christmas, the viewing of the Nativity play is one of the oldest Christmastime traditions, with the first reenactment of the Nativity of Jesus taking place in A.D.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In that year, Francis of Assisi assembled a Nativity scene outside of his church in Italy and children sang Christmas carols celebrating the birth of Jesus.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Each year, this grew larger, and people travelled from afar to see Francis' depiction of the Nativity of Jesus that came to feature drama and music.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Nativity plays eventually spread throughout all of Europe, where they remained popular.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas Eve and Christmas Day church services often came to feature Nativity plays, as did schools and theatres.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In France, Germany, Mexico, and Spain, Nativity plays are often reenacted outdoors in the streets.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Many families have been decorating their houses with lights and in modern times, inflatables, to create a festive environment.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The origin of Christmas lights began with candles on Christmas trees in 16th-century Germany, where they symbolized Christ as the light of the world.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The earliest extant specifically Christmas hymns appear in fourth-century Rome.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Latin hymns such as *"Veni redemptor gentium"*, written by Ambrose, Archbishop of Milan, were austere statements of the theological doctrine of the Incarnation in opposition to Arianism.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] *"Corde natus ex Parentis"* ("Of the Father's love begotten") by the Spanish poet Prudentius (died 413) is still sung in some churches today.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the 9th and 10th centuries, the Christmas "Sequence" or "Prose" was introduced in North European monasteries, developing under Bernard of Clairvaux into a sequence of rhymed stanzas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the 12th century the Parisian monk Adam of St.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Victor began to derive music from popular songs, introducing something closer to the traditional Christmas carol.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas carols in English appear in a 1426 work of John Awdlay who lists twenty five "caroles of Cristemas", probably sung by groups of 'wassailers', who went from house to house.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The songs now known specifically as carols were originally communal folk songs sung during celebrations such as "harvest tide" as well as Christmas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] It was only later that carols began to be sung in church.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Traditionally, carols have often been based on medieval chord patterns, and it is this that gives them their uniquely characteristic musical sound.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Some carols like "Personent hodie", "Good King Wenceslas", and *"In dulci jubilo"* can be traced directly back to the Middle Ages.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] They are among the oldest musical compositions still regularly sung.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] *"Adeste Fideles"* (O Come all ye faithful) appeared in its current form in the mid-18th century.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The singing of carols increased in popularity after the Protestant Reformation in the Lutheran areas of Europe, as the Reformer Martin Luther wrote carols and encouraged their use in worship, in addition to spearheading the practice of caroling outside the Mass.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The 18th-century English reformer Charles Wesley, a founder of Methodism, understood the importance of music to Christian worship.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In addition to setting many psalms to melodies, he wrote texts for at least three Christmas carols.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The best known was originally entitled "Hark!
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] How All the Welkin Rings", later renamed "Hark!
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas seasonal songs of a secular nature emerged in the late 18th century.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The Welsh melody for "Deck the Halls" dates from 1794, with the lyrics added by Scottish musician Thomas Oliphant in 1862, and the American "Jingle Bells" was copyrighted in 1857.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Other popular carols include "The First Noel", "God Rest Ye Merry, Gentlemen", "The Holly and the Ivy", "I Saw Three Ships", "In the Bleak Midwinter", "Joy to the World", "Once in Royal David's City" and "While Shepherds Watched Their Flocks".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the 19th and 20th centuries, African American spirituals and songs about Christmas, based in their tradition of spirituals, became more widely known.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] An increasing number of seasonal holiday songs were commercially produced in the 20th century, including jazz and blues variations.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In addition, there was a revival of interest in early music, from groups singing folk music, such as The Revels, to performers of early medieval and classical music.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] One of the most ubiquitous festive songs is "We Wish You a Merry Christmas", which originates from the West Country of England in the 1930s.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Radio has covered Christmas music from variety shows from the 1940s and 1950s, as well as modern-day stations that exclusively play Christmas music from late November through December 25.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Hollywood movies have featured new Christmas music, such as "White Christmas" in *Holiday Inn* and *Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Traditional carols have also been included in Hollywood films, such as "Hark!
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The Herald Angels Sing" in *It's a Wonderful Life* (1946), and "Silent Night" in *A Christmas Story*.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] A special Christmas family meal is traditionally an important part of the holiday's celebration, and the food served varies greatly from country to country.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Some regions have special meals for Christmas Eve, such as Sicily, where 12 kinds of fish are served.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the United Kingdom and countries influenced by its traditions, a standard Christmas meal includes turkey, goose or other large bird, gravy, potatoes, vegetables, sometimes bread, cider, and, in more recent decades, nut roast.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Special desserts are also prepared, such as Christmas pudding, mince pies, fruit cake and Yule log cake.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In Poland and Scandinavia, fish is often used for the traditional main course, but richer meat such as lamb is increasingly served.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In Sweden, it is common with a special variety of smörgåsbord, where ham, meatballs, and herring play a prominent role.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In Germany, France, and Austria, goose and pork are favored.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Beef, ham, and chicken in various recipes are popular worldwide.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The Maltese traditionally serve *Imbuljuta tal-Qastan*, a chocolate and chestnuts beverage, after Midnight Mass and throughout the Christmas season.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Slovenes prepare the traditional Christmas bread potica, *bûche de Noël* in France, *panettone* in Italy, and elaborate tarts and cakes.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] *Panettone*, an Italian type of sweet bread and fruitcake, originally from Milan, Italy, usually prepared and enjoyed for Christmas and New Year in Western, Southern, and Southeastern Europe, as well as in South America, Eritrea, Australia and North America.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The eating of sweets and chocolates has become popular worldwide, and sweeter Christmas delicacies include the German *stollen*, marzipan cake or candy, and Jamaican rum fruit cake.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] As one of the few fruits traditionally available to northern countries in winter, oranges have been long associated with special Christmas foods.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Eggnog is a sweetened dairy-based beverage traditionally made with milk, cream, sugar, and whipped eggs (which gives it a frothy texture).
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Spirits such as brandy, rum, or bourbon are often added.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The finished serving is often garnished with a sprinkling of ground cinnamon or nutmeg.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas cards are illustrated messages of greeting exchanged between friends and family members during the weeks preceding Christmas Day.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The traditional greeting reads "wishing you a Merry Christmas and a Happy New Year", much like that of the first commercial Christmas card, produced by Sir Henry Cole in London in 1843.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The custom of sending them has become popular among a wide cross-section of people with the emergence of the modern trend towards exchanging E-cards.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas cards are purchased in considerable quantities and feature artwork, commercially designed and relevant to the season.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The content of the design might relate directly to the Christmas narrative, with depictions of the Nativity of Jesus, or Christian symbols such as the Star of Bethlehem, or a white dove, which can represent both the Holy Spirit and Peace on Earth.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] A number of nations have issued commemorative stamps at Christmastide.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Postal customers will often use these stamps to mail Christmas cards, and they are popular with philatelists.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] These stamps are regular postage stamps, unlike Christmas seals, and are valid for postage year-round.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] They usually go on sale sometime between early October and early December and are printed in considerable quantities.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas seals were first issued to raise funding to fight and bring awareness to tuberculosis.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The first Christmas seal was issued in Denmark in 1904, and since then other countries have issued their own Christmas seals.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The exchanging of gifts is one of the core aspects of the modern Christmas celebration, making it the most profitable time of year for retailers and businesses throughout the world.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] On Christmas, people exchange gifts based on the Christian tradition associated with Saint Nicholas, and the gifts of gold, frankincense, and myrrh which were given to the baby Jesus by the Magi.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Talley holds that the Roman Emperor Aurelian placed the alternate festival on December 25 in order to compete with the growing rate of the Christian Church, which had already been celebrating Christmas on that date first.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] A number of figures are associated with Christmas and the seasonal giving of gifts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Among these are Father Christmas, also known as Santa Claus (derived from the Dutch for Saint Nicholas), Père Noël, and the Weihnachtsmann; Saint Nicholas or Sinterklaas; the Christkind; Kris Kringle; Joulupukki; tomte/nisse; Babbo Natale; Saint Basil; and Ded Moroz.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The Scandinavian tomte (also called nisse) is sometimes depicted as a gnome instead of Santa Claus.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The best known of these figures today is the red-dressed Santa Claus, of diverse origins.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The name 'Santa Claus' can be traced back to the Dutch *Sinterklaas* ('Saint Nicholas').
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Nicholas was a 4th-century Greek bishop of Myra.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Among other saintly attributes, he was noted for the care of children, generosity, and the giving of gifts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] His feast day, December 6, came to be celebrated in many countries with the giving of gifts.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Saint Nicholas traditionally appeared in bishop's attire, accompanied by helpers, inquiring about the behaviour of children during the past year before deciding whether they deserved a gift or not.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] By the 13th century, Saint Nicholas was well known in the Netherlands, and the practice of gift-giving in his name spread to other parts of central and southern Europe.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] At the Reformation in 16th- and 17th-century Europe, many Protestants changed the gift bringer to the Christ Child or *Christkindl*, corrupted in English to 'Kris Kringle', and the date of giving gifts changed from December 6 to Christmas Eve.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The modern popular image of Santa Claus, however, was created in the United States, and in particular in New York.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The transformation was accomplished with the aid of notable contributors including Washington Irving and the German-American cartoonist Thomas Nast (1840–1902).
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Following the American Revolutionary War, some of the inhabitants of New York City sought out symbols of the city's non-English past.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] New York had originally been established as the Dutch colonial town of New Amsterdam and the Dutch Sinterklaas tradition was reinvented as Saint Nicholas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In Italy's South Tyrol, Austria, the Czech Republic, Southern Germany, Hungary, Liechtenstein, Slovakia, and Switzerland, the Christkind (Ježíšek in Czech, Jézuska in Hungarian and Ježiško in Slovak) brings the presents.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Greek children get their presents from Saint Basil on New Year's Eve, the eve of that saint's liturgical feast.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Nikolaus is not identical with the Weihnachtsmann (who is the German version of Santa Claus / Father Christmas).
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Nikolaus wears a bishop's dress and still brings small gifts (usually candies, nuts, and fruits) on December 6 and is accompanied by Knecht Ruprecht.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Although many parents around the world routinely teach their children about Santa Claus and other gift bringers, some have come to reject this practice, considering it deceptive.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Multiple gift-giver figures exist in Poland, varying between regions and individual families.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] St Nicholas (*Święty Mikołaj*) dominates Central and North-East areas, the Starman (*Gwiazdor*) is most common in Greater Poland, Baby Jesus (*Dzieciątko*) is unique to Upper Silesia, with the Little Star (*Gwiazdka*) and the Little Angel (*Aniołek*) being common in the South and the South-East.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Grandfather Frost (*Dziadek Mróz*) is less commonly accepted in some areas of Eastern Poland.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] It is worth noting that across all of Poland, St Nicholas is the gift giver on Saint Nicholas Day on December 6.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas during the Middle Ages was a public festival with annual indulgences, including sporting.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] When Puritans outlawed Christmas in England in December 1647 the crowd brought out footballs as a symbol of festive misrule.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The Orkney Christmas Day Ba' tradition continues.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the former top tier of English football, home and away Christmas Day and Boxing Day double headers were often played guaranteeing football clubs large crowds by allowing many working people their only chance to watch a game.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Champions Preston North End faced Aston Villa on Christmas Day 1889 and the last December 25 fixture was in 1965 in England, Blackpool beating Blackburn Rovers 4–2.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] One of the most memorable images of the Christmas truce during World War I was the games of football played between the opposing sides on Christmas Day 1914.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] There are several theories as to why December 25 was chosen as the date for Christmas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] However, according to theology professor Susan Roll, liturgical historians agree that it was linked in some way with "the sun, the winter solstice and the popularity of solar worship in the later Roman Empire".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In Roman tradition, December 25 was deemed to be the winter solstice and March 25 the spring equinox, dates that retained significance despite Julian calendar drift.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Greco-Roman writers in the second and third centuries called December 25 the birth day of the Sun.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The early Church linked Jesus to the Sun and referred to him as the 'true Sun' or 'Sun of Righteousness'.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the early fifth century, Augustine of Hippo and Maximus of Turin preached that it was fitting to celebrate Christ's birth at the winter solstice, because it marked the point when the hours of daylight begin to grow.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The use of solar imagery for Christ is understood as part of broader cosmological symbolism in late antiquity, and may not have been direct cultic borrowing.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The 'history of religions' or 'substitution' theory proposes that the Church chose December 25 as Christ's birthday (*dies Natalis Christi*) to appropriate the Roman winter solstice festival *dies Natalis Solis Invicti*, the birthday of the god *Sol Invictus* (the 'Invincible Sun').
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] It had been held on this date since 274 AD; before the earliest evidence of Christmas on December 25.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Professor Gary Forsythe says that the *Natalis Solis Invicti* followed "the seven-day period of the *Saturnalia* (December 17–23), Rome's most joyous holiday season since Republican times, characterized by parties, banquets, and exchanges of gifts".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Roll says that "the specific nature of the relation" between Christmas and the *Natalis Solis Invicti* has not yet been "conclusively proven from extant texts".
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The 'calculation theory' proposes that the date arose from Christian chronography rather than from an effort to supplant a pagan festival.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] It was first proposed by Louis Duchesne.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Some early Christians marked Jesus's death on the day before Passover, the 14th of Nisan.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Several third‑century sources correlate this with the spring equinox on March 25.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Duchesne conjectured that early Christians believed Jesus was conceived and died on the same date, yielding a March 25 conception and December 25 birth nine months later.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] However, he admitted that this belief is not found in any early Christian text.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The earliest attestation of a December 25 Nativity may be contemporaneous with or earlier than clear attestations of a December 25 Sol Invictus festival.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Some jurisdictions of the Eastern Orthodox Church, including those of Russia, Georgia, North Macedonia, Montenegro, Serbia, and Jerusalem, mark feasts using the older Julian calendar.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Since Christmas 1899 until Christmas 2099 inclusive, there is a difference of 13 days between the Julian calendar and the modern Gregorian calendar.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] As a result, December 25 on the Julian calendar currently corresponds to January 7 on the calendar used by most governments and people in everyday life.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Therefore, the aforementioned Orthodox Christians mark December 25 (and thus Christmas) on the day that is internationally considered to be January 7.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Therefore, these Orthodox Christians mark December 25 (and thus Christmas) on the same day that is internationally considered to be December 25.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The Armenian Apostolic Church continues the original ancient Eastern Christian practice of celebrating the birth of Christ not as a separate holiday, but on the same day as the celebration of his baptism (Theophany), which is on January 6.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] This is a public holiday in Armenia, and it is held on the same day that is internationally considered to be January 6, because since 1923 the Armenian Church in Armenia has used the Gregorian calendar.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] However, there is also a small Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem, which maintains the traditional Armenian custom of celebrating the birth of Christ on the same day as Theophany (January 6), but uses the Julian calendar for the determination of that date.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] As a result, this church celebrates "Christmas" (more properly called Theophany) on the day that is considered January 19 on the Gregorian calendar in use by the majority of the world.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Ukraine officially moved its Christmas date from January 7 to December 25, to distance itself from the Russian Orthodox Church that had supported Russia's invasion.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] This followed the Orthodox Church of Ukraine formally adopting the Revised Julian calendar for fixed feasts and solemnities.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] There are four different dates used by different Christian groups to mark the birth of Christ, given in the table below.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas is typically a peak selling season for retailers in many nations around the world; sales increase dramatically during this time as people purchase gifts, decorations, and supplies to celebrate.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the United States, the "Christmas shopping season" starts as early as October.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In Canada, merchants begin advertising campaigns before Halloween (October 31) and step up their marketing following Remembrance Day on November 11.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the UK and Ireland, the Christmas shopping season starts from mid-November, around the time when high street Christmas lights are turned on.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] A concept devised by retail entrepreneur David Lewis, the first Christmas grotto opened in Lewis's department store in Liverpool, England in 1879.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the United States, it has been calculated that a quarter of all personal spending takes place during the Christmas/holiday shopping season.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Figures from the US Census Bureau reveal that expenditure in department stores nationwide rose from $20.8 billion in November 2004 to $31.9 billion in December 2004, an increase of 54 percent.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In other sectors, the pre-Christmas increase in spending was even greater, there being a November–December buying surge of 100 percent in bookstores and 170 percent in jewelry stores.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the same year employment in American retail stores rose from 1.6 million to 1.8 million in the two months leading up to Christmas.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Industries completely dependent on Christmas include Christmas cards, of which 1.9 billion are sent in the United States each year, and live Christmas trees, of which 20.8 million were cut in the US in 2002.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In the UK in 2010, up to £8 billion was expected to be spent online at Christmas, approximately a quarter of total retail festive sales.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In most Western nations, Christmas Day is the least active day of the year for business and commerce; almost all retail, commercial and institutional businesses are closed, and almost all industries cease activity (more than any other day of the year), whether laws require such or not.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] In England and Wales, the Christmas Day (Trading) Act 2004 prevents all large shops from trading on Christmas Day.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Similar legislation was approved in Scotland in 2007.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Film studios release many high-budget movies during the holiday season, including Christmas films, fantasy movies or high-tone dramas with high production values to hopes of maximizing the chance of nominations for the Academy Awards.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] One economist's analysis calculates that despite increased overall spending, Christmas is a deadweight loss under orthodox microeconomic theory, because of the effect of gift-giving.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] This loss is calculated as the difference between what the gift giver spent on the item and what the gift receiver would have paid for the item.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] It is estimated that in 2001, Christmas resulted in a $4 billion deadweight loss in the US alone.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Because of complicating factors, this analysis is sometimes used to discuss possible flaws in current microeconomic theory.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Other deadweight losses include the effects of Christmas on the environment and the fact that material gifts are often perceived as white elephants, imposing cost for upkeep and storage and contributing to clutter.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] Christmas has been the subject of controversy and attacks from various sources, both Christian and non-Christian.
[src:a-silent-agreement/christmas-p02] The Parliament of Scotland, which was dominated by Presbyterians, passed a series of acts outlawing the observance of Christmas between 1637 and 1690; Christmas Day did not become a public holiday in Scotland until 1871.
